Question: What makes a sales professional an effective problem solver?
Answer (from AnswerId): Asking enough high yield questions to truly understand the needs of a customer, Being in the business long enough to know how to overcome objections, Someone who “touches the desk” during each opportunity to utilize management support, Telling the customer you are willing to go above and beyond for them
respuesta correcta Texto: Asking enough high yield questions to truly understand the needs of a customer
feedbackText:
We believe that being a Sales Professional has some similarities to being a doctor. You should diagnose before you prescribe. For this reason, the interview stage and your ability to be a problem solver may well be the most crucial part of the sales process.  
To be an effective problem solver, you need to ask enough high yield questions to truly understand the needs of a customer. 
There are several strategies you can use to improve your interviewing and problem solving skills:
SPACED
Determine product requirements using the SPACED acronym:
Safety
Performance
Appearance
Comfort
Economy
Dependability
SPIN
During the Reverse Vehicle Walkaround, you should learn how to SPIN. 
The acronym SPIN, made famous by writer and sales scientist Neil Rackman, stands for: 
Situation - Ask questions that help you understand the situation that brought your customer in
Problem - How has their situation created a problem in their mind
Implication - What are the implied needs and potential cost (what will it cost them financially or emotionally)
Need Payoff - You must specifically demonstrate to them how purchasing your vehicle solves their problem and thus negates or reduces the need to shop elsewhere

Take the time with your customer to learn more about their current vehicle. The current vehicle is familiar to your customer which can bring an element of comfort to the conversation. This allows the customer to “open up” and share what they liked and disliked about their current vehicle.

Understanding Persuasion
Being a Good Storyteller
Be Persistent

Be Remarkable
Make Every Customer Feel like a VIP

Question: How can understanding persuasion benefit you in the sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): Customers will buy from you without having to offer them the best price you can , Customers will have the perception of control while you guide them through the process, You don’t have to ask as many questions because you’re in control of the sales process, You’re able to close a sale quicker and more efficiently
respuesta correcta Texto: Customers will have the perception of control while you guide them through the process
feedbackText:
Persuasion is a powerful element which allows a customer to perceive they are in control while we guide them through our sales process.
People would much rather be persuaded to believe and do things than to simply be told to do so. In addition, in order for someone to do business with us, they must first know us; they must like us; they must trust us.
Trust is key for persuasion. Without trust, your customers won’t have confidence in what you’re sharing.  With trust, they’ll believe in you and see things from your point of view.

Question:
A couple walk into the dealership. You notice that they’re visibly tanned and wearing sunhats.
What should you do to help make yourself more accessible?
Answer (from AnswerId): Any of the above, Compliment them on their tans and tell a joke about the time you got a sunburn in Mexico, Greet them and ask what brings them into the dealership today, Talk about the weather and how nice it’s been lately
respuesta correcta Texto: Compliment them on their tans and tell a joke about the time you got a sunburn in Mexico
feedbackText:
Your personal story makes you most accessible to customers. Don’t be seen as a salesperson; be seen as a person who is there to help. 
Coffee table books about pets or sports, pictures of family, and vacations are a great way to start to tell your story.
People want to do business with people they know, like, and trust. Share a few stories about your life and past customer experiences, and you’re on the way to selling more vehicles. 
Don’t be afraid to tell a personal story about yourself, or share a joke even, as long as it's appropriate.
These types of things can help humanize the interaction and allow for a deeper connection with the customer.

Question: How are persistence and pressure used differently in the sales?
Answer (from AnswerId): If we’re too persistent it will put too much pressure on the customer, Persistence is a mindset you should have and a little well-timed pressure is productive, There is no difference in sales. These are considered the same thing, You should allow persistent customers to go outside the sales process rather than putting them under pressure
respuesta correcta Texto: Persistence is a mindset you should have and a little well-timed pressure is productive
feedbackText:
A mindset of continuous effort in spite of difficulty or opposition often succeeds over any objections that the customer may have.    
Unfortunately, customers don’t always want to go through our process. The resistance we receive from our customers to move through our sales process is real.  
Persistence is a mindset you should have and a little well-timed pressure on your customers is productive in the process.
We must be creative and agile in how we persist numerous times as we deal with customer resistance. Having the mindset to continue and not give up at the first sign of resistance is critical.
Finding unique ways to ask the same questions, when faced with customer resistance, is a useful skill in persistence.

Question: How would you best demonstrate persistence in the automotive sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): Asking for the order over and over and over again, Finding unique ways to ask or answer the same questions when faced with customer resistance, Ignoring customer resistance by marching forward though the sales process, Press management over and over until they give your customer the deal they want
respuesta correcta Texto: Finding unique ways to ask or answer the same questions when faced with customer resistance
feedbackText:
Finding unique ways to ask and answer the same questions, when faced with customer resistance, is a useful skill in persistence.
For example, addressing a question about interest rates could easily derail the sales process. By addressing the question and asking to proceed back to the presentation, you are applying your persistence to stay the course.
Customer asks, “What is the interest rate?”
You reply, “This is our preferred rate of X%. Is the interest rate important to you?”
Customer responds, “Yes. Of course.”
You ask, “Is there a rate you were looking for?”
Customer replies, “Yes. The model X has 0% financing available.”
You reply, “We can provide rate comparisons on any model for you to consider. That being said, shall we proceed with the vehicle presentation?”

Question: Persistence and building value are:
Answer (from AnswerId): Closely related concepts, Only somewhat related to one another, Vastly different concepts
respuesta correcta Texto: Closely related concepts
feedbackText:
A successful opportunity relies on whether or not we can build enough value and earn enough trust from a customer to ask for their business.  
Our ability to persist and take a customer through each of the steps in the sales process will have a significant impact on how successful we are. 
If we aren’t able to accomplish each of the steps, we’ve most likely missed out on building the value and trust required for someone to do business with us.

Finding unique ways to ask or answer the same questions, when faced with customer resistance, is a useful skill in persistence.
For example, addressing a question about interest rates could easily derail the sales process. By addressing the question and asking to proceed back to the presentation, you are applying your persistence to stay the course.
Customer asks, “What is the interest rate?”
You reply, “This is our preferred rate of X%. Is the interest rate important to you?”
Customer responds, “Yes. Of course.”
You ask, “Is there a rate you were looking for?”
Customer replies, “Yes. The model X has 0% financing available.”
You reply, “We can provide rate comparisons on any model for you to consider. That being said, shall we proceed with the vehicle presentation?”

Question: What is a “key flipper”?

feedbackText:
Most salespeople are "key flippers" and prefer to let the customer take the vehicle out on their own. This bad habit leads to no control and in some cases the customer coming back from the drive and giving the keys and dealer plate to front reception, leaving and not even saying goodbye. You can kiss your deal goodbye! 
It’s important to maintain control and create a high level test drive experience that creates excitement by demonstrating key aspects of the vehicle--this can only be achieved when you go with the customer.

Question: Based on the decades long success of the Guiness Book of World Record breaking automotive salesperson Joe Girard, what is the fundamental factor to having influence over a customer?
Answer (from AnswerId): Create scarcity, Establish authority, Get commitment early, Getting someone to like you
respuesta correcta Texto: Getting someone to like you
feedbackText:
Joe Girard sold an average of 5 vehicles a day during his peak. 
He had over 13,000 customers he was in regular contact with. When asked many times about his secret he pointed to that fact that he was able to get his customers to like him and then the rest was easy. 
Today is a different car business but one thing is certain, you can be the most dedicated and technically sound rep but if your prospects don’t like you, you’ll be constantly fighting an uphill battle.

Question:
Do your best to frame all negotiations as a collaborative effort. Instead of seeing you as an opponent, the prospect will see you as a:
A. Trusted advisor
B. Friend
C. Teammate
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, All of the above, B and C
respuesta correcta Texto: A and C
feedbackText:
One of the six weapons of influence is to get customers to like you. One way to accomplish this is to do your best to frame all negotiations as a collaborative effort. Instead of seeing you as an opponent, the prospect will see you as a trusted advisor or teammate.
If your outcome is tied directly to the customer, let them know you share a common goal. 
If you are required to touch base with a Sales Manager, frame the interaction as you and the customer vs the Sales Manager. 
Accomplish this, and the prospect will like you more.

Question: Getting customers to like you is key to your sales success. Therefore, if you see an opportunity to pay them a compliment, you should always go for it.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
Paying compliments can be a dangerous game. Be disciplined. Complimenting someone's physicality can easily be misconstrued or offensive. Never overdo it. Laying it on too thick is transparent and will have the opposite effect you want.
Casually and genuinely, look for small behaviours or tastes that you appreciate, then let your prospect know in the normal flow of conversation. Do not force this aspect; it's not worth the risk.

Question: How could you utilize the Law of Reciprocation in your sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): Let them know that you’ll do something special to help them out, Offer the customer a beverage when they sit down with you, Provide them with a fuel gift card if they buy from you today, Any of the above

feedbackText:
The Law of Reciprocation is an ancient and unwritten social rule that you must not take without giving in return.
When someone does something nice for you, there is a deep rooted psychological obligation to do something nice in return. 
It's simple but powerful, and It could be behavioural, a gift, or a service.
Make simple gestures like offering a beverage or offer some sincere advice on how to proceed. This may compel them to return the favour later in the sale.
There are two crucial points to consider when using the Law of Reciprocity. The primary is to go first; be the first to give. 
Next is to ensure that whatever gift you give, make it personalized and unexpected.

Question:
In a series of experiments in restaurants, Dr. Robert Cialdini observed that when the server gave diners a single mint at the end of their meal about the same time they brought their bill, tips increased by approximately 3%.
This illustrates the weaponization of:
Answer (from AnswerId): Authority, Liking, Reciprocation, Social Proof
respuesta correcta Texto: Reciprocation
feedbackText:
Dr. Robert Cialdini illustrates this social and psychological phenomenon in multiple ways throughout his many writings. 
One, in particular, should hit home with most of us.
In a series of experiments in restaurants, he observed Reciprocation weaponized. The last time you went out for dinner, you likely had a server give you a gift. 
I'll bet it was about the same time they brought your bill. A mint perhaps, a small gift for your child or maybe a fortune cookie? 
Here's the question. Does a small, timely gift influence the tip you leave the server? Most people will say no. But that mint can make a huge impact. 
In the experiment, giving diners a single mint at the end of their meal increased tips by approximately 3%. 
More surprisingly, if the server leaves two candies, tips don't double. They quadruple to a 14% increase in the gratuity. 
Most interestingly, though, is that if the server provides one mint, begins to leave, pauses, returns and says, "Some extra mints for my favourite customers of the day" (or something similar), it's like gratuity rocket fuel.
A staggering 23% increase, showing there's nuance to Reciprocity. 
It's not merely the gift, service, or advice, but how you give it.

Question:
People feel a strong drive to follow through on things they had previously agreed to. This is called the Law of Consistency. 
What is caused when this doesn’t happen?
Answer (from AnswerId): Cognitive Connectivity, Cognitive Contribution, Cognitive Discordance, Cognitive Dissonance
respuesta correcta Texto: Cognitive Dissonance
feedbackText:
In a now-famous series of experiments, researchers asked homeowners in a neighbourhood if the homeowner was willing to put a large, unattractive Drive Safe sign prominently on their front lawn. 
As you can imagine, not many agreed to the request even though it was for the good of the community at large. 
In a nearby neighbourhood, 400% as many homeowners agreed to the request. How could this be? By using the Law of Consistency. 
In the two weeks before asking people to erect the giant sign, the researchers made several smaller requests of the neighbours — first, a postcard-sized card in their front window. A week later, a little sign on the front lawn. 
By the time the researchers requested the large, unattractive sign of the homeowners, the decision-maker was already the type of person who publicly supported Safe Driving in the community. 
To not follow through would create what is called Cognitive Dissonance. In basic terms, the homeowner felt a strong psychological compulsion to be consistent.

A. A friend
B. A family member
C. A salesperson
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, A only, Any of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and B
feedbackText:
A personal recommendation from a trusted friend or family member that you know shares your values is what Wisdom of Your Friends is all about. 
It's not hard to imagine that this may be the singular most compelling version of Social Proof.
When the purchase is more significant, trust becomes essential. Although the other versions of Social Proof all have their place and can be extremely useful, nothing beats having someone you know, like, and trust looking you straight in the eye and telling you that buying XYZ is a great decision. 
For this reason, any sales professionals worth their salt should ALWAYS ask for referrals at the end of each successful sale, and every customer, before they leave, should be fully aware of any incentives or programs you have to reward referrals in the future.

Question: Overt authority is far more effective if it comes from which of the following sources?
Answer (from AnswerId): A third party, Another salesperson, Your manager, Yourself
respuesta correcta Texto: A third party
feedbackText:
When people are unsure, they tend to follow the lead of credible experts. 
Science supports that calling attention to anything that enhances your credibility will help to induce trust. 
It's also clear that you should always signal all credentials before your first attempt at influencing someone. Credentials can include a mix of things such as certificates or diplomas, licenses, and awards, etc. These signals can be overt or done more subtly.
Keep in mind that overt authority is far more effective if the credibility is coming from a third party and not just you tooting your own horn. 
Some may find subtle Authority signals to be more manipulative than the overt version. 
Designers of this subtle variation hide them in plain sight. Many of these tactics have included doctors, both real and fake.

feedbackText:
Science tells us to display credentials, honours, or expertise. Make sure they are coming from a third party or are in evidence as certificates, awards, diplomas, and more. 
Trust indicators brought up after you attempt to persuade may not have the desired effect. Authority = credibility = trust, and when you inspire confidence, you are more than halfway there.

Answer (from AnswerId): Pointing to the sticker price on the vehicle you respond by saying “I understand, the best price has been been determined by the manufacturer, and that price is on the sticker of this vehicle.", Pointing to the sticker price on the vehicle you say “I understand, all our vehicles are value priced, and the best price comes at your time of commitment, was there a price that you had in mind?”, Putting your hands up (surrendering) you respond by saying “I understand, the best price comes at your time of commitment. Question: _______ questions allow you to listen and better assist the customer.

respuesta correcta Texto: Open-ended
feedbackText:
Open-ended questions allow you to listen and better assist the customer as you move forward (for example, during the needs analysis). An example of an open-ended question is, “Can you tell me more about why that is important to you?”
Closed-ended questions are generally answered with one-word answers and are often used to get confirmation to move onto the next step of the sale (or to regain control of the process). An example of a closed-ended question is, “I’m more than happy to get a brochure. Just before I do… can I ask you, is this your first visit to our dealership?”

Question:
There are 5 key steps to the sales process: Meet & Greet, Interview, Vehicle Selection, Presentation, and Demonstration.
Which of the following is the sixth additional step?
Answer (from AnswerId): Closing Presentation, Personal Conversation, Price Presentation, Reverse Walkthrough
respuesta correcta Texto: Price Presentation
feedbackText:
Over the years it's been well established that there are five key steps to the sales process. Being able to control each of these steps will maximize your chances of success. 
The five key steps are:
Meet & Greet: Make a good first impression
Interview: Learn specifically about what the customer needs
Vehicle Selection: Land the customer on a vehicle that meets or exceeds their needs
Presentation: Do a needs based, benefit driven presentation of your product
Demonstration: Allow them to test and experience your product
An additional step is:
6. Price Presentation: Show them 3-4 options on how they can own your product. (Include a lease payment)

Five Key Steps in the Sales Process:
Over the years it's been well established that there are five key steps in the sales process. Following these steps will maximize your chances of success. 
The Five Key Steps are:
Meet & Greet: Make a good first impression
Interview: Learn specifically about what the customer needs
Vehicle Selection: Land the customer on a vehicle that meets or exceeds their needs
Presentation: Perform a needs-based, benefit-driven presentation of your product
Demonstration: Allow the customer to test and experience your product

Question: What does it mean to Road Map for control?
Answer (from AnswerId): Being specific about what will happen and asking permission to move forward, Explaining the test drive route, Letting your customer know what you’d like to do and asking them to follow , Taking your customer through the sales process from Meet and Greet to Close
respuesta correcta Texto: Being specific about what will happen and asking permission to move forward
feedbackText:
Road Map for Control:
Alleviating anxiety and fear in the customer is a powerful strategy for sales professionals. 
Road Mapping is the best-known method to achieve this. It leads to the customer feeling in control. Aside from increased closing percentages, it creates a significant bump in customer satisfaction.
To Road Map, you need to be specific about what will happen and ask permission to move forward. 
Note: Gaining agreement from the customer is not the same as “dragging” them through the process with a “follow me” strategy.

Both question types have value and utility. 
Open-ended questions allow you to listen and better assist the customer as you move forward (for example, during the needs analysis). An example of an open-ended question is, “Can you tell me more about why that is important to you?”
Closed-ended questions are generally answered with a single word. They are often used to get confirmation to move onto the next step of the sale, or to regain control of the process. feedbackText:
Gaining Control:
Gaining control early in the sales process (while giving the customer the perception they are in control) is the key. Then, and only then, can you create a win-win with your customer. 
Control in the sales process is the ability to regulate, direct, or influence the outcome of said process or event.

Question: Controlled Apathy is a state of listening and _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): awareness, communicating, control, worry
respuesta correcta Texto: awareness
feedbackText:
As you listen to the dripping tap, your emotions rise from Apathy to the next emotional level called Controlled Apathy. Controlled Apathy is the state of listening and awareness. 
Customers arrive at the dealership in a state of Controlled Stress and it’s our job to bring them down to Controlled Apathy as we begin the sales process. 
However, when it comes time to make a decision, if they are in the Controlled Apathy stage, they won’t make it! They need to go back to the Controlled Stress state to decide to buy.

Question: Controlled stress represents the threshold of:
Answer (from AnswerId): Confidence, Control, Decision making, Engagement
respuesta correcta Texto: Decision making
feedbackText:
Controlled stress represents the threshold of decision making. As you are lying in bed considering the dripping tap, controlled stress happens as soon as your feet hit the floor. Total decisiveness. Anything less and you stay in bed and continue to listen to the dripping tap.
It’s important to understand and manage emotions throughout the sales process. If a customer is in Controlled Apathy at the decision stage, they won't make it. They need to be in Controlled Stress to make a decision.
Conversely, they won't move into the sales process in a state of High Stress. We must be able to navigate through the various stages of emotions to effectively manage the sale.

Question:
High Stress is considered to be the fourth Level of Emotion. It could also mean:
A. They are frustrated
B. They are angry
C. They are ready to make a decision
Answer (from AnswerId): A or B, A or C, Any of the above, B or C
respuesta correcta Texto: A or B
feedbackText:
There is a fourth Level of Emotion - High Stress. In some cases, this could mean frustration or anger. 
Would you ever want to bring your customers to the level of High Stress? The obvious answer is no. Keep in mind, when you start talking about money with people, things can begin to change the way people feel very quickly.

Question:
The Four States of Emotion are: 
Apathy
Controlled Apathy
Controlled Stress
High Stress
What State are most customers in when they first engage with a Product Advisor at the dealership?
Answer (from AnswerId): Apathy, Controlled Apathy, Controlled Stress, High Stress
respuesta correcta Texto: Controlled Stress
feedbackText:
Controlled Stress is the state most customers are in when they first engage with a Product Advisor at the dealership. 
It’s important we do a good job at the Meet and Greet to win the customers' confidence. 
They must feel as though they have 'won', so their stress starts to come down from Controlled Stress, to Controlled Apathy (the listen and awareness state)
If we aren’t able to do this, we risk them jumping into High Stress and losing the opportunity before we even really had a shot.

feedbackText: We can describe Apathy as the lowest form of human emotion. Can we reach this state daily? Of course, the answer is yes - usually in the evening time.

However, when it comes time to make a decision, if they are in the Controlled Apathy stage, they won’t make one! 
Controlled Stress represents the threshold of decision making. They need to go back to a Controlled Stress state to decide to buy.

Question:
Change, control, and tension are the three factors that affect emotions which are the ingredients of productivity.
How do you create the highest level of acceptable tension and, at the same time, maintain high levels of customer satisfaction?
Answer (from AnswerId): By controlling the process, By creating tension, With price, With the test drive
respuesta correcta Texto: With price
feedbackText:
This is the million-dollar question.
The answer = PRICE! Think about it for a moment. Without price, there can never be a decision to buy!
Customers, from time to time, will come into a dealership and decide to purchase; without even driving the vehicle. It happens!
On the other hand, one thing that will never happen is a customer coming into a dealership and making a decision to purchase without first looking at numbers to determine if the price is right before they make their final decision. IT HAS NEVER HAPPENED!

Question: How does tension play a role in the sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): It allows you to regulate, direct, or influence the outcome of a process or event, It is the critical ingredient which determines what changes will be made and when those changes will take place, It should be avoided as it negatively impacts customer satisfaction and your ability to close the deal

feedbackText:
Tension is the level of physical, emotional, and intellectual activity a person is experiencing at any given moment in time. 
It is the critical ingredient which determines what changes will be made and when those changes will take place. In the absence of tension, there is no productivity.
To close a deal, you need to be able to evoke a decision from the customer. If you do not ask for the order chances are you will be less likely to sell a car. If you ask for the order too soon or too late the sale will likely be lost!

Question: In the absence of tension, there is no _______.

Question: Customers in today’s market are better qualified than ever before. The majority of customers will spend _______ weeks researching their purchase online.
Answer (from AnswerId): 1 to 2, 2 to 3, 3 to 5, 4 to 7
respuesta correcta Texto: 4 to 7
feedbackText:
Step 3 of the sales process used to be waiting for customers to get out of their vehicle and “land on a car.” Today, selection is much more! 
Vehicle selection today is genuinely where the numerical negotiations should begin. Customers in today’s market are better qualified than ever before. 
The majority of customers will spend 4 to 7 weeks researching their purchase online and will only end up physically visiting one or two dealerships, tops.

Question: What is the best method to manage price expectations with customers?
Answer (from AnswerId): Presenting only vehicles that have similar costs, Providing your lowest available price with the presentation, Using a budget worksheet when closing the deal, Using a pricing menu before the presentation and demo
respuesta correcta Texto: Using a pricing menu before the presentation and demo
feedbackText:
Managing price expectations before vehicle presentation and demonstration will go a long way to increase your overall closing ratio! It is far more effective to use a menu pricing system and to negotiate inventory upfront as opposed to price later on. 
Customers have created an expectation of the price they want to pay. By merely providing a pricing menu before the presentation and demo, you will build credibility and your customers will have the opportunity to confirm a sense of affordability and set the right expectations upfront long before the negotiations of price or payment begin!

Question:
A customer comes in and tells you they have already selected a vehicle with a specific trim package. They have a price they are willing to pay based on what they saw online.
What potential challenge may result from this?
Answer (from AnswerId): The vehicle they selected may not be available in the colour they want, They may not have factored in taxes and dealer costs in the price and can’t afford the vehicle they selected, This is not a challenge as you will be able to match them with a vehicle they like for a price they can afford
respuesta correcta Texto: They may not have factored in taxes and dealer costs in the price and can’t afford the vehicle they selected
feedbackText:
Managing price expectations before vehicle presentation and demonstration will go a long way to increase your overall closing ratio! It is far more effective to use a menu pricing system and to negotiate inventory upfront as opposed to price later on. 
Ask yourself this question: How much gross profit does it cost you to help move a customer from a higher trim level at higher payment to a lower trim level at a more economical payment upfront? 
Consider this approach compared to a negotiation where you may only find that the price of the vehicle is out of their budget.
Good luck trying to be profitable when you find out the customer did not factor taxes and dealer costs during their research online.

Step 3 of the sales process used to be waiting for customers to get out of their vehicle and “land on a car.” Today, selection is much more! 
Vehicle selection today is genuinely where the numerical negotiations should begin. Customers in today’s market are better qualified than ever before. The majority of customers will spend 4 to 7 weeks researching their purchase online and will only end up physically visiting one or two dealerships, tops. 
When these customers show up and walk through the showroom doors, in many cases they are ready to buy! A big part of their decision today is how well a dealership handles the price.

You must become a “Right to a price dealership.” Create a pricing menu allowing customers to confirm affordability and consistency with their online research.

Question: What are customer convictions?
Answer (from AnswerId): Customer’s core belief system, Key features that a customer must have, Specific brand of vehicle , Trim level that makes sense

feedbackText:
It’s important we don’t mix up convictions with “nice to haves”. There are certain features that MUST be equipped for the customer on their next vehicle.
For example, it would be nice to have a 3,000 lb tow capacity, but if they have absolutely no need to tow ANYTHING, then it’s not a true conviction. However, if you know your customer tows a utility trailer and a fishing boat the tow capacity will absolutely be a conviction for your customer.

Question:

A. The customer can become confused
B. The customer can land on a vehicle that’s too expensive

Many sales people make the mistake of presenting and driving multiple vehicles to try and confirm selection through elimination. 
This typically leads to the customer becoming confused and or landing on a vehicle that ends up being too expensive. This can also lead to the manager having to price out multiple vehicles which almost always leads to lower same day closing ratios and poor Back ratios.

Customer – "Yes, but before the presentation, is the Value Price the best you can do?"
Salesperson – "Good question! What you are asking me is, are we flexible, am I correct?"
Customer - "Yes."
Salesperson – "Yes, we are flexible, but flexibility today is more than the price of the vehicle, it can be in the down payment, monthly payments and terms. Are not all areas of price important to you before any final decision on this vehicle?”
Customer - "No, I just want the best price!"
Salesperson – "I understand. There are many different areas of flexibility, beyond the price, that we can work through together. Keeping that in mind, and assuming the price will not be a problem, should we not confirm the vehicle before your commitment to the final price?"
Move forward to the vehicle presentation, or if they’re persistent on getting the best price, “touch desk” with the sales manager and then return to selling!

Question: What does “stop the shop” refer to?
Answer (from AnswerId): Identifying a key customer conviction that your vehicle has over the competition, Leveraging a better pricing and financing package than the competition offers, Uncovering the customers needs and wants during the interview process, Using negotiation tactics to close the deal on the same day rather than have the customer delay it

feedbackText:
Knowing your competition is a helpful tool.  Knowing the differentiators between your lineup and the competition's lineup is another level. In some cases, we are able to “stop the shop” simply by identifying a key customer conviction that your vehicle has over the competitive model.
An example for a safety conscious buyer could be how your base trim level includes blind spot detection and lane change assist. The competitive model requires a jump in price and trim to have similar safety features.

Question: Anytime you hear a customer complain, you need to ensure you qualify the complaint by asking, "Would that be a deal-breaker?".

respuesta correcta Texto: True
feedbackText:
Whether you are selling the vehicle on a walkaround or a demonstration drive, you need to be on the lookout for DEAL-BREAKERS! 
Deciphering between a complaint and a deal-breaker is crucial. Anytime you hear a customer complain, you need to ensure you qualify the complaint by asking, "Would that be a deal-breaker?" 
If the customer said no and was complaining or commenting, MOVE ON! If the customer says yes, then you need to find a solution to the problem. In some cases, you may have to switch them to a different vehicle altogether.

Understanding the difference between a complaint and a true-deal breaker is key. Addressing these comments with your customer, followed by a request to continue moving forward in the process is called “the Art of the Bypass”.

feedbackText:
If a customer does not want to shake your hand and you put them on the spot are you really giving yourself the best opportunity to create a positive first impression? Customers are deciding in less than seven seconds if they are going to give you the opportunity to work with them or not.

Question: What is one key element about your appearance that will make the customer feel more comfortable?

respuesta correcta Texto: Name tag
feedbackText:
The second A stands for APPEARANCE! For the flash of a second that the customer looks you up and down are you recognisable as an employee of your dealership? 
Many stores will help create a team based environment by having team uniforms. This helps the customer better identify who is there to help them and at the same time it helps create a team based atmosphere.

feedbackText:

You have two appointments and two deliveries and as you start to prepare your deliveries all of the sudden a customer stops you in the showroom and asks you where the parts department is located.
Do you try to direct them verbally on how to find the parts department? Or do you figuratively take them by the hand, guide them to the parts department and introduce them to your parts representative?
The latter is of course the right answer! Do you have your MOJO on and are you ready to help every customer? 
Do you see every customer as a valued opportunity believing that if guided through the right sales process that they are here to make a decision today? Or are you plate glass qualifying and trying to judge a book by its cover?
Outside of the sales process or lack thereof one of the key deciding factors on who will win the sales board and who will be at the bottom of the sales board is ATTITUDE! 
As a sales professional you should be happy to help every customer!

Question: The more we learn about the specific needs and wants of our customers, the higher the _______ we bring as a salesperson.
Answer (from AnswerId): empathy, experience, professionalism, value
respuesta correcta Texto: value
feedbackText:
Step two, the interview, is arguably the most critical in the sales process.  In this step, we must ask open-ended questions, create common ground, talk about the trade, confirm likes and dislikes and build a bond of trust. 
Whether we conduct a good interview can often determine whether we sell a vehicle or not. The more we learn about the specific needs and wants of our customers, the higher the value we bring as a salesperson. The more value we bring to the table, the greater the obligation our customers will have to purchase.  
Too often, salespeople drill customers with "canned," repetitive questioning, which has a negative impression. A genuine interest in this investigation stage is a must.

Question: What does SPACED stand for?

feedbackText:
By using the acronym SPACED (Safety, Performance, Appearance, Comfort, Economy, Dependability), we can easily identify what is most important to the customer in their next vehicle purchase.
When we know what is important to the customer we’re able to tailor our presentation highlighting the features, advantages and benefits that line up perfectly with what they’re looking for. Instead of presenting a “canned'' presentation for every customer that walks in, we’re able to personalize the  walkaround their needs keeping engagement at the highest level.
If we spend all our time talking about pound feet of torque, horsepower and engine displacement to a grandmother who is most concerned with keeping her grandchildren safe in the car, we’re missing the mark.

Question:
Not everyone who is involved in the decision for a vehicle purchase is present. You offered to take the vehicle to the person that is not there but your customer rejected this offer.
What other strategy can you employ?
Answer (from AnswerId): Third party interview , Book future appointment, The art of bypass, The blind close
respuesta correcta Texto: Third party interview
feedbackText:
The second strategy to use when a decision maker is not present is the "Third-party interview." You interview the person that is not there through the person that is there. 
"Mr. Customer, I hope your wife Sabrina has a great day at work! Understanding she is an integral part of the decision making, what features has she enjoyed the most in your current vehicle? Ok! Leather, heated seats and sunroof. Provided we can find a vehicle that has all the features you and your wife are looking for, would I be able to get you some pricing so you can take the numbers home and think things over?" 
Now that the customer realizes that you are working with them and not just trying to sell them a vehicle that same day, they will likely be more open to sharing.

Question: What is the primary strategy when all parties are not present to the sale?
Answer (from AnswerId): Offer the “puppy dog” approach where the customer takes the vehicle overnight , Offer to physically take the vehicle of interest with the customer to the other party that needs to be involved, Provide service to the customer and book an appointment for when both parties are available , Provide so much value that they’ll make a decision without consulting their spouse or partner

feedbackText:
Sometimes, not everyone who is involved in the decision making is present. These are called One-Legged Buyers. If all parties are not present to the sale, the probability of selling a vehicle the same day or the next day is unlikely.
One strategy you can use to overcome this is to offer to take the vehicle to the party that is not present. If accepted, in many cases it turns into a sale! If rejected, you still need to attempt to involve the person that is not there.

Question: Finding the area of price that is the most valuable to a customer, relates to which aspect of the negotiation process?
Answer (from AnswerId): Creating a position, Determining the customer’s position, Gaining an agreement, Isolating to a unit of one
respuesta correcta Texto: Isolating to a unit of one
feedbackText:
When discussing price with customers, it’s important that you confirm and work through these four critical aspects of the negotiation:
1. Isolate to a unit of one:
What area of the price is most important to the customer? Is it the value price (MSRP)? Trade? Down payment or payments? Are you able to identify the customer's condition?
2. Create a position (Dealership Value Price): 
Are you highlighting and sharing the dealership's position?
3. Determine the opposing position, which is the price the customer can afford to pay. This is also known as the customer blueprint:
Is the customer's blueprint clearly defined?
4. Gain an agreement! Ask for the business: 
Before approaching your sales manager’s desk, did you ask for the order?
Identifying these above aspects of the negotiation allows you and your desk manager to determine what kind of buyer you are dealing with.

feedbackText:
When discussing price with customers, it’s important that you confirm and work through the critical aspects of negotiation.

Question:
Which of these are types of buyers during a negotiation?
A. Conditional
B. Preliminary
C. Unconditional
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, B and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and C
feedbackText:
There are two different types of buyers during a negotiation:
Conditional Buyer: A customer with a trade-in will always represent a conditional buyer. Without a trade, one of the other three areas of the price will be stated as their condition for buying (value price, down payment, monthly payment).
Unconditional Buyer: If they’re not trading, and if there is no desire to share which area of price is most important to them, you are likely dealing with an unconditional buyer.

Question: Which of these best describes who a conditional buyer is?
Answer (from AnswerId): A customer that requests a price adjustment, A customer that requires a cash incentive to purchase, A customer that will only purchase a specific vehicle model and trim, A customer with a stated price condition for purchasing
respuesta correcta Texto: A customer with a stated price condition for purchasing
feedbackText: Customers with a trade-in will always represent a conditional buyer. However, without a trade, one of the other three areas of the price will be stated as their condition for buying (value price, down payment, monthly payment).

Question: Which of these best describes who an unconditional buyer is?
Answer (from AnswerId): A customer that is unsure of what they’re looking for in a vehicle, A customer that requires a prize incentive to purchase, A customer that will purchase regardless of the price presented, A customer that won’t state their price condition for purchasing
respuesta correcta Texto: A customer that won’t state their price condition for purchasing
feedbackText: Customers that are not trading, and have no desire to share which area of price is most important to them are likely unconditional buyers.

Question: What happens during the price negotiation process if an offer IS in-profit?
Answer (from AnswerId): A deal should be determined to be in profit or not before the negotiation process begins, Your sales manager will advise you on how to negotiate the deal to create an even larger profit margin, Your sales manager will help you send a write-back with an option close, Your sales manager will immediately send you back to the customer to close
respuesta correcta Texto: Your sales manager will help you send a write-back with an option close
feedbackText:
Once you have figured out that a customer is committed to buying, you then determine whether a deal is in-profit or not in-profit.
If the deal is in-profit, your sales manager will help you send a write-back with an option close.

Question: What happens during the price negotiation process if an offer is NOT in-profit?
Answer (from AnswerId): A deal should be determined to be in profit or not before the negotiation process begins, Your sales manager will reduce the customer’s requested price adjustment by half and send you back to close, Your sales manager will reject the deal and send you back to close the customer on a different vehicle, Your sales manager will reject the deal and send you back with a “sorry close”
respuesta correcta Texto: Your sales manager will reject the deal and send you back with a “sorry close”
feedbackText:
Once you have figured out that a customer is committed to buying, you then determine whether a deal is in-profit or not in-profit.
If the offer is not in-profit, your sales manager will  reject the offer and send you back with a “'sorry close." Many customers don't understand the size of the discount they may have requested. 
They’ll then roll back to the price adjustment (discount) necessary to show what it would take to achieve the customer’s desired deal at the desk.

C. $1000 down option with an increase in length of payment terms to reduce the customer’s monthly payments
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, All of the above, B and C
respuesta correcta Texto: A and B
feedbackText:
After determining that a deal is in-profit, and once you’ve sent the write-back with the option close, your options now come into the mix:  
Option 1: Present the required down payment necessary to achieve the customer's desired payment over the suggested term, even if they asked for $0 down.) You'll also include additional terms for flexibility and contrast.
Option 2: $0 down option with a payment increase over the suggested terms. Include additional terms options for flexibility and contrast.

Question:

respuesta correcta Texto: A, B, and C
feedbackText:
When rolling back the price adjustment on a "sorry close", you have four areas of flexibility:
Increasing the down payment
Increasing the monthly payment
Extending the payment terms
Offer another vehicle with fewer features at a lower cost

Question:
You’re working with a customer and have already determined that the deal is NOT in-profit.

How should you continue the conversation with your customer?

The great news is we have four areas of flexibility we can consider.”, “Mr./Mrs. Customer, my manager appreciates your offer. However, given that the vehicle is value priced and we have limited margins, we can look at a certified used vehicle today instead to stay within your budget.”, “Mr./Mrs. Customer, my manager appreciates your offer. respuesta correcta Texto: “Mr./Mrs. Customer, my manager appreciates your offer. However, given that the vehicle is value priced and we have limited margins, my manager is sorry. The great news is we have four areas of flexibility we can consider.”
feedbackText:
Presenting the “sorry close” to customers requires a skillful response from you, and should look something like this: 
Salesperson: "Mr./Mrs. Jones, my manager appreciates your offer. However, given that the vehicle is value-priced and we have limited price margins, my manager is sorry. (insert short pause) The great news is we have four areas of flexibility we can consider. We can look at increasing the down payment, we can also look at increasing the monthly payment, we can extend the term, or if you prefer we can look at another vehicle with fewer features at a lower cost. Mr./Mrs. Jones, would you consider looking at a different vehicle?" 
Customer: "No, this is the vehicle I want." 
Salesperson: "I understand. Should we look at increasing the down payment or the monthly payment?"

Question: Why is it important to discover a customer’s condition to purchase and turn them into a conditional buyer?

feedbackText:
Unconditional buyers are people who typically request a pricing breakdown, including the lease and finance payments, and any cash deal incentives. They usually like to "take all the information home and think things over." 
Without discovering the customer’s condition to purchase, you have no way of closing towards this condition. If there’s no rejection, there’s no way to work to a deal!

Question: Which of these is an important point to explain to customers if they’re hesitant on putting money down?
Answer (from AnswerId): As the down payment goes down, monthly payments go up, As the down payment goes down, the length of the terms has to increase, Down payments are generally required on most vehicle purchases, Most dealerships offer rebate incentives to customers that purchase with a down payment
respuesta correcta Texto: As the down payment goes down, monthly payments go up
feedbackText:
For customers that may be hesitant to putting money down upfront, you should navigate the conversation like so: 
Salesperson:"Mr. and Mrs. Jones, my manager has taken the liberty of working numbers with a $3500 down payment. Based on $3500 down, we have various payment options, starting with 24-month financing for only $1,094 or a 24-month lease option for only $411 per month. Which one of these payment options works best for you?" Wait and listen for a response!
Customer: "We like the 60-month finance for $485, but we don't want to put any money down."
Salesperson: Strokes out the $3500 down, writes the customer's desired $0 down payment in its place, then circles the 60-month payment.
Salesperson: "Mr. and Mrs. Jones, I can work with that! Please keep in mind that typically when the down payment goes down, the monthly payment goes up. How much over $485 would you consider paying?"
Customer: "We don't want to go over $485 per month!"
Salesperson: "I understand. Based on $0 down, if I can find a way to achieve payments of no more than $485 per month, how would you handle your deposit today? Visa, MasterCard, or debit?”
Customer: "Here is my Visa, but tell your manager we do not want to go over 60 months!"
Salesperson: "I appreciate your offer. I will do my best!"

feedbackText: Monthly payment amounts can be a difficult obstacle to overcome. This is usually the biggest deciding factor in a customer’s affordability.

Question:
You’re working with a customer during the price negotiation process.
They mention that the down payment amount is too much.
How should you continue the conversation with this customer?
Answer (from AnswerId): Ask them what an acceptable down payment would be, Ask them whether they want to lease or finance, as that will affect their down payment amount, Inform them of the down payment amount required to stay within their monthly budget, Show them payment terms based on $0 down payment
respuesta correcta Texto: Ask them what an acceptable down payment would be
feedbackText:
Down payment amounts may be a sticking point for some customers. They may be insistent on providing $0 down without realizing how placing even a small amount down may reduce their monthly payments.
Flow the conversation similar to this:
Customer: “The down payment is too much!”
Salesperson: “I understand. What down payment did you have in mind?”
Customer: "I was thinking $0, but I could put $1,000 down."
Salesperson: "I can work with that! Based on $1,000 down, are you thinking about lease or finance today?”
Customer: "Lease over 48 months."
Salesperson: "Excellent choice! Keep in mind that as the down payment goes down, the monthly payment goes up. How much over $372 would you consider paying?"
Customer: "$400 is our budget."
Salesperson: "Could I say not to exceed $419?"
Customer: "$410 is our max!"
Salesperson: "Based on $1,000 down, and if I can confirm your monthly payment of $410, how would you handle your deposit today? Visa, MasterCard, or debit?

Question:

respuesta correcta Texto: Discover what the customer’s max price is and try work within that range
feedbackText:

Flow the conversation similar to this:
Customer: "Is the Value Price (MSRP) the best you will do?"
Salesperson: "As a salesperson, I can only sell the vehicle at the value price. Having said that, my sales manager decides the final price. Is there a price that you had in mind?"
Customer: "I want a $500 discount! I can't pay more than $23,500 plus the dealer fees and taxes."
Salesperson: "Up to?"
Customer: "$23,500 is my max!"
Salesperson: "If I can confirm your $23,500, plus the dealer fees and taxes, how would you like to handle your deposit today? Visa, MasterCard, or debit?”

Question: How should you respond to a customer asking about your interest rates?
Answer (from AnswerId): Ask about their preferred interest rate first, Ask the customer about their monthly affordability first, Disclose your interest rate first, Don’t disclose your interest rate
respuesta correcta Texto: Disclose your interest rate first
feedbackText:
Customers that are aware of better interest rates being provided through another dealership could be insistent on receiving the same rate. 
It’s important to address this and show the customer how your dealership can match, or be comparable to the monthly payments they would receive elsewhere.
Flow the conversation similar to this:
Customer: “What is the interest rate?”
Salesperson: Respond by disclosing the actual rate. Confirm the customer's desired interest rate. Offer to work their vehicle of choice using their desired interest rate, and then negotiate the difference between payments. Remember, you can't win an interest rate battle, but you can win with payment!

Question: How should you work with a customer that compares your interest rate with another dealership’s rate?

respuesta correcta Texto: Show the customer their payments between both rates
feedbackText:
Customers that are aware of better interest rates being provided through another dealership could be insistent on receiving the same rate. 
It’s important to address this and show the customer how your dealership can match, or be comparable to the monthly payments they would receive elsewhere.
Flow the conversation similar to this:

Customer: "Yes, of course!"

Customer: "Yes, that would be helpful."

Question: What might be a good way to present longer payment terms to a customer during the price negotiation process?

feedbackText: Extending the terms of a lease or financing can make it difficult for customers to wrap their head around owning a vehicle for that long. Focusing on the monthly price reduction to the customer can make this easier to digest.

Question: How did the rising price of vehicles impact trends in the finance industry?

respuesta correcta Texto: The length of financing terms increased
feedbackText:
In the '60s and '70s, vehicle prices increased and dealerships respectively introduced 36 and 48-month terms to help keep the monthly cost of financing the same. 
However, customer loyalty dropped significantly during this time frame. The average ownership tenure increased to roughly 57 months and only 30% of customers were returning to the same dealership to purchase a vehicle. 
Luckily, population increases created the need for families to own two vehicles, which increased overall consumer demand.

Question: How does the product of lease make it easier for customers to relate the costs?
Answer (from AnswerId): Leasing payments are similar to one’s they may have had previously, Leasing reduces the monthly payment cost compared to financing, Leasing has less of a time commitment so they automatically see the savings, Leasing has no mechanical overhead costs
respuesta correcta Texto: Leasing payments are similar to one’s they may have had previously
feedbackText:
Qualifying customers as potential lessee’s is an important part of the sales process.
While leasing itself doesn’t have many barriers to entry, it’s key to introduce price early on in the selection process. This allows the customer to determine their affordability before the presentation.
The product of lease lets the customer relate to similar monthly payments they currently have or have had in the past.
However, when comparing a lease and financing on a dollar for dollar basis, leasing is more expensive. 
Disclosure is truthful and it’s always better that we disclose the total cost comparison in advance.
Leasing isn’t about the payment you're making, it’s about the payment you’re not making.

Question: Trade-ins are applied to the full value of the vehicle when a customer decides to lease.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
Trades can affect payments when financing as well as leasing.
Customers with a trade-in vehicle may be initially more inclined to purchase, as they already own the vehicle they’re looking to trade.
However, they may benefit more by leasing, as the trade value is applied to the depreciated portion of the vehicle (the residual value) and not the full sales price.
This gives a proportionally larger payment reduction compared to trading in and financing.
For example: 10 (full retail value for purchase) divided into 2 is 5, but 3 (depreciation retail value for what the lease payment is based on) divided into 2 is 1.5.

Question: How did the rising price of vehicles impact trends in the finance industry?
Answer (from AnswerId): Customers held onto the same vehicle for longer, Monthly payment prices went up each decade, Overall vehicle sales declined, The length of financing terms increased
respuesta correcta Texto: The length of financing terms increased
feedbackText:
In the '60s and '70s, vehicle prices increased and dealerships respectively introduced 36 and 48-month terms to help keep the monthly cost of financing the same. 
However, customer loyalty dropped significantly during this time frame. The average ownership tenure increased to roughly 57 months and only 30% of customers were returning to the same dealership to purchase a vehicle. 
Luckily, population increases created the need for families to own two vehicles, which increased overall consumer demand.

Question: What is a benefit of higher vehicle turnover rates?
Answer (from AnswerId): Greater customer loyalty, Lower vehicle prices, More potential customers
respuesta correcta Texto: Greater customer loyalty
feedbackText:
In the 1950’s, financing for automobiles was limited to 24 months and customers only retained ownership of the same vehicle for about 27 months on average.
This high turnover cycle created exceptional customer loyalty, as drivers were experiencing little to no mechanical issues during their ownership tenure.

Question: What was the maximum length of vehicle financing in the 1950s?
Answer (from AnswerId): 12 months, 18 months, 24 months, 36 months
respuesta correcta Texto: 24 months
feedbackText:
In the 1950’s, financing for automobiles was limited to 24 months and customers only retained ownership of the same vehicle for about 27 months on average.
This high turnover cycle created exceptional customer loyalty, as drivers were experiencing little to no mechanical issues during their ownership tenure.

Question: At its peak, what was the approximate market penetration rate for vehicle leasing?
feedbackText:
The 80’s and 90’s continued to bring challenges to the auto industry, as inflation and price increases saw the introduction of 60 and 72 month financing. 
Monthly payments could no longer stay at previous levels and for the first time in over 30 years, they increased.
Leasing was introduced more heavily during this time to offset these cost increases. At one point, leasing represented approximately 50% of all vehicle financing!

feedbackText:
Today, vehicle financing has reached unprecedented lengths. Customers are now financing over 84, and in some cases, 96 months to pay off their vehicle loans!
Talking to your customers about the benefits of leasing has never been more of a necessity.

Question: How does leasing free up more cash flow for a customer?
Answer (from AnswerId): By reducing their monthly payment amounts compared to same term financing, By reducing their monthly payment amounts compared to financing, By requiring a lower down payment compared to financing, There are no obligations for them to repair a leased vehicle
respuesta correcta Texto: By reducing their monthly payment amounts compared to same term financing
feedbackText:
When considering the length of vehicle financing nowadays, most customers probably won’t ever pay off their vehicles. 7+ years is a long time to consider a commitment to anything, let alone a vehicle!
Reducing the terms of an obligation can free up more cash flow for a customer in the long term, which in turn reduces their debt obligations. I.e. 36 months leasing versus 84 months financing.

Question: Compared to vehicle financing, leasing provides _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): more options, lower costs, more obligations, more restrictions
respuesta correcta Texto: more options
feedbackText:
Compared to vehicle financing, a short term lease, at similar monthly payments to long term financing, has more options at the end of the term. 
For example: After 24 months with a lease, you can either drop the lease off or buy out the rest of the lease; trade and upgrade. With financing, your customers will still have roughly 60 more months of remaining payments.
Leasing just provides more flexibility to a customer!

Question: The residual value of a vehicle is flexible.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: True
feedbackText:
Leasing doesn’t encumber a customer’s worth statements, which opens their credit line for more flexibility when making other life decisions.
The residual value of a leased vehicle is flexible as long as it goes down. Residual values are preset by lending guides and they will not increase. 
Higher kilometer allowances and variable payment choices can help reduce the residual value of the vehicle. This also lets you present the customer with multiple quotes to assist them in choosing the payment that best suits their driving needs.

Question: When does the true equity in a lease begin?
Answer (from AnswerId): First month , 2/3 through term, End of term, There is no equity in lease
respuesta correcta Texto: First month
feedbackText:
Leased vehicles generally require no down payment to achieve relatively low monthly payments. 
Long term equity value is achieved earlier due to non-capitalized taxes.
The true “equity” in cash flow savings begins in the first month, and this is because of the reduction in the number monthly payments the customer will have to make with a lease. Again, comparing a 36 month term to an 84 month one.

Question: All service work on a leased vehicle must be performed by the original dealership.
Answer (from AnswerId): True, False
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
Leasing doesn’t encumber a customer’s worth statements, which opens their credit line for more flexibility when making other life decisions.
The residual value of a leased vehicle is flexible as long as it goes down. Higher kilometer allowances and variable payment choices can hold full value to the capital cost.
The service on a leased vehicle can also be performed by any authorized dealership. It does not need to be performed by the same dealership that the vehicle was leased from.
Note: The lessee is responsible for ensuring all vehicle service has documented records to not void the vehicle’s warranty.

Question: Estate planning is a spin off benefit of which feature of lease?
Answer (from AnswerId): Flexibility, Better records, Credit line enhancement , Guaranteed Asset by reducing their monthly payment amounts compared to financing
respuesta correcta Texto: Flexibility
feedbackText:
Taxes on a lease are non-capitalized, which means that they are only calculated based on the obligation of the term. The taxes on the residual value of the vehicle won’t be realized until the lease is bought out at the end of the term. 
This can provide additional flexibility when considering leasing or financing. For example, a much lower down payment is required due to the non-capitalization of taxes. This presents less of a risk to lenders. 
The cost of early termination is also less expensive in lease than in purchase / finance because of the non-capitalization. This could be a major benefit to a customer who is considering estate planning.

Question: With regards to leasing and income tax, which of these statements is correct?
Answer (from AnswerId): Income tax is a non-issue in vehicle lease, If you’re in business, do not lease, Leasing is not for working people, You have to be in business to lease
respuesta correcta Texto: Income tax is a non-issue in vehicle lease
feedbackText:
With regards to taxation, leasing provides several benefits and little to no issues.
For example, income tax is a non-issue in vehicle leasing, as the CRA deductibility of business use vehicles is the same whether you lease or finance.
Monthly statements are also available without charge and there’s no depreciation schedule required for business use taxation.

Question: To be a lease the following three things are required.
Answer (from AnswerId): Contract, Vehicle, Insurance, Goods, Contract, Lessee, Goods, Time, Money, Lessee, Lessor, Dealership
respuesta correcta Texto: Contract, Vehicle, Insurance
feedbackText:
Goods, time, and money are the three things that make up a contract, and a lease is no different.
The “goods” in this case is the vehicle itself, the time is the length of the lease, and the money is the total value of the leased vehicle, under the terms of the agreed upon contract.

Question: Which of the following statements is most correct in regards to leasing?
Answer (from AnswerId): Leasing rolls the price back 6 years, Leasing disguises the true price of the car from the customer, Leasing is designed for cash buyers, Leasing is only for business owners
respuesta correcta Texto: Leasing rolls the price back 6 years
feedbackText:
When you look at it in this way, leasing creates a price program that rolls vehicle pricing back to an affordable level that customers may have been previously used to. The price of vehicles has gone up and terms of financing haven’t been extended beyond 96 months.
Leasing essentially takes the price of a car today, and rolls it back six years to a price the customer can relate to. Their new lease payments become more relatable to when they may have last purchased a vehicle!

Question: What can be the main factor in a customer’s decision to buy or lease?
Answer (from AnswerId): The price of each option, The effect of each on their credit rating, The length of the term, The potential asset value
respuesta correcta Texto: The price of each option
feedbackText: Selling the idea of a lease to your customers can be a difficult task, as price is ultimately the main factor in a customer’s decision to buy or lease. As well, the majority of customers who walk away without purchasing do so because of the price.

respuesta correcta Texto: Lease is not about the payment you will be making; it’s about the payment you won’t be making
feedbackText:
When you look at it in this way, leasing creates a price program that rolls vehicle pricing back to an affordable level that customers may have been previously used to. 
Leasing essentially takes the price of a car today, and rolls it back six years to a price the customer can relate to.
While it may be more expensive in the short term, leasing is not about the payment you will be making; it’s about the payment you won’t be making.
Ask them what they can do to help with their overall finances by having that additional cash flow every month? Will they be able to pay off their credit cards, save for an RESP or RRSP?

The “goods” in this case is the vehicle itself, the time is the length of the lease, and the money is the total value of the leased vehicle, under the terms of the agreed upon contract.

Question: In regards to lease terminations, which of the following statements is correct?
Answer (from AnswerId): A vehicle lease may be terminated early by agreement between the lessor and lessee, A vehicle lease may be terminated early by agreement between the lessor and lessee, provided a termination penalty is paid, If the lessor wants to terminate the lease early, they return the vehicle to the dealership, You can not have an early termination in a vehicle lease
respuesta correcta Texto: A vehicle lease may be terminated early by agreement between the lessor and lessee
feedbackText:
A lease contract only requires an agreement between the lessee and lessor. 
Lease contract terminations can come in many different forms and, if agreed upon, the lease could be terminated early.
Some lease termination events are more difficult to approach than others and it's important to know how your customers will be affected.

Question: In the event of an accident and subsequent write off, the vehicle’s mileage will be:
Answer (from AnswerId): Prorated based on contracted mileage per year of contract, Not considered if customer replaces vehicle with new lease, Recorded accurately at time of accident, Reflected in the next lease agreement
respuesta correcta Texto: Prorated based on contracted mileage per year of contract
feedbackText:
Unfortunately, accidents do happen and in some cases the vehicle may be written off.
A write-off is when the damages to the vehicle exceed the value of the costs to repair it. When a write-off occurs, the lease contract is cancelled. Any mileage on the vehicle is then prorated. 
For example: A vehicle is written off at the 24 month mark. The vehicle’s mileage is 60,000 KMs. 
60,000 divided by 24 months equals 30,000 KMs per year. If the lease was contracted at 24,000 KMs per year, the lessee would have a mileage liability.

Question: In the event of theft of a leased vehicle, When is the lease contract terminated?
Answer (from AnswerId): The date the loss was declared , The beginning of the next month, The date of next payment, The date of the theft
respuesta correcta Texto: The date the loss was declared
feedbackText:
In the event that a leased vehicle is stolen, the contract would be terminated on the date the loss was declared. 
This is why it’s extremely important that your customers contact both the authorities and the leasing company as soon as they’re aware of the theft.
Insurance companies then have up to 45 days to declare a loss. 
Note: The lessee is still responsible for any lease payments during this period.

Question: The term “Lease Holding” refers to what?
Answer (from AnswerId): The available equity within a lease contract, A dealer controlled lease contract before being assigned to the financing institute, The holding company that is responsible for the lease contract, The property value of a lessor
respuesta correcta Texto: The available equity within a lease contract
feedbackText:
The most common form of lease termination is a contract expiry.
At the end of their lease term, your customer has the option to:
Extend their lease
Return the leased vehicle
Buy out their leased vehicle
Re-leasing the vehicle will extend the payments for a few months. The outstanding balance will decrease and the vehicle will continue to depreciate.
Returning the vehicle will close out the contract. The customer then pays any mileage overages or unclaimed damages to the vehicle, as agreed upon in their lease. If the lessor sells their vehicle at lease end for more than the contracted residual value, the difference can create a lease holding.
If a dealer wishes to work with a lease for mutual benefit, they can create a lease holding. This happens when the dealer sells the vehicle for more than the residual value.
In turn, excess funds are paid to the lessee as a refund on rentals paid. In many provinces, it may also qualify for a tax credit.
They can also buy out the vehicle at its residual value. It can either be purchased in cash or financed like a used vehicle.

Question: In the event that a leased vehicle is stolen, it’s crucial that your customers contact:
Answer (from AnswerId): Both of the above, Neither of the above, The authorities, The leasing company
respuesta correcta Texto: Both of the above
feedbackText:
In the event that a leased vehicle is stolen, the contract would be terminated on the date the loss was declared. 
This is why it’s extremely important that your customers contact both the authorities and the leasing company as soon as they’re aware of the theft.
Insurance companies then have up to 45 days to declare a loss.

Question: When the damages to a vehicle exceed the value of the costs to repair it, it’s called:
Answer (from AnswerId): A write-off, A reverse equity situation, A waiver of depreciation, A write-on
respuesta correcta Texto: A write-off
feedbackText: A write-off is when the damages to the vehicle exceed the value of the costs to repair it. When a write-off occurs, the lease contract is cancelled. Any mileage on the vehicle is then prorated.

Question: Anyone under the age of 19 cannot drive a leased vehicle.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
Provincial or state laws determine which insurance providers operate within their region. The providers then decide who is eligible for which coverage and what their rates will be.
Some car insurance providers may offer additional liability protections within their policies. 
It’s up to the customer to know what their insurance does or does not cover.
Note: It’s important to note that for the purposes of leasing, a valid driver's license insured under lessee’s insurance is the only requirement to operate a leased vehicle.

Question: How does waiver of depreciation insurance protect the customer?
Answer (from AnswerId): The customer is provided with a cheque for the full value of the lost vehicle, The customer is able to receive a replacement vehicle and continue their financing term as normal, The customer’s obligation to their contract is voided, The residual value of the vehicle is doubled and provided to the customer as a cheque
respuesta correcta Texto: The customer is provided with a cheque for the full value of the lost vehicle
feedbackText:
Waiver of depreciation is an option negotiated with lending institutions to help customers avoid potentially owing more on a vehicle than what it’s worth (known as reverse equity refinance.) 
This works by allowing the insurance company to waive the ability to deduct any depreciation of value and provide the customer with a cheque for the full value of the lost vehicle. This generally requires the purchase of a substitute vehicle with the insurance settlement.
The cost for this type of insurance depends on the size of the loan.
This needs to be arranged when a customer has made the decision to purchase and before they take delivery of the vehicle.

Question: Substitution of collateral helps a customer when which of these is not present?
Answer (from AnswerId): The waiver of depreciation insurance was not purchased, Their insurance has lapsed and they’ve failed to renew it, They have insufficient insurance coverage to cover a settlement by court, When their insurance only covers personal use and not business use
respuesta correcta Texto: The waiver of depreciation insurance was not purchased
feedbackText:
Waiver of depreciation is an option negotiated with lending institutions to help customers avoid potentially owing more on a vehicle than what it’s worth (known as reverse equity refinance.) 
This works by allowing the insurance company to waive the ability to deduct any depreciation of value and provide the customer with a cheque for the full value of the lost vehicle. This generally requires the purchase of a substitute vehicle with the insurance settlement.
The cost for this type of insurance depends on the size of the loan.
This needs to be arranged when a customer has made the decision to purchase and before they take delivery of the vehicle.

Question: Guaranteed Asset Protection (GAP) insurance offers which of these benefits?
Answer (from AnswerId): GAP protects from any reverse equity in the loss or destruction of a vehicle, but doesn’t protect any equity that you may have already put into the vehicle , GAP ensures that you will be able to replace your vehicle at the same payment, regardless of what happens to the vehicle, GAP is total protection from loss or destruction of a vehicle, If a vehicle is lost or destroyed, a replacement vehicle will be provided at the same lease payment
respuesta correcta Texto: GAP protects from any reverse equity in the loss or destruction of a vehicle, but doesn’t protect any equity that you may have already put into the vehicle
feedbackText:
No provisions for replacement, subject to conditions of mileage, payment, etc.  
Any down payment, or trade-in used as a down payment, to reduce the monthly payment isn’t protected within the GAP protection.

Question: Which of these are protected with Guaranteed Asset Protection (GAP) insurance?
Answer (from AnswerId): Neither of the above, Any down payment, Any trade-in used as a down payment, Both of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: Neither of the above
feedbackText:
GAP insurance is an optional type of coverage that provides the difference between the actual cash value of a customer’s car, and the amount they owe to a lender or leasing company at the time of a claim.
Any down payment, or trade-in used as a down payment, to reduce the monthly payment isn’t protected within the GAP protection.

Question: Liability protection (Ontario) is limited by which of the following?
Answer (from AnswerId): The region the accident took place in, Personal eligibility, The amount protection in the policy, The insurance company
respuesta correcta Texto: The region the accident took place in
feedbackText: Provincial or State laws determine the extent of liability to lease company or lessee.
