respuesta correcta Texto: “If the right deal came along, and we could get you a great value for your trade, would you consider trading your vehicle in?”
feedbackText:
You should follow a script relatively similar to this:
Rep: “Good morning. May I speak with Mr. Jones, please?”
Customer: “Speaking.”
Rep: “Hi Mr. Jones. This is <your first name> calling from <dealership name>. How are you today?”
Customer: “Good.”
Rep: “The reason for my call today is that I wanted to confirm your appointment for <insert appointment day/time>.”
Customer: “Great, thanks for reminding me.”
Rep: “Terrific! The other reason for my call is I want to ask you a couple of quick questions about your vehicle. Would that be ok?”
Customer: “Sure.”
Rep: “I was wondering if you still have approximately 60,000km on your vehicle?”
Customer: “I think it’s closer to 65,000km.”
Rep: “Great! Does your vehicle have leather or cloth interior?”
Customer: “Leather.”
Rep: “Perfect! And what colour is your vehicle?”
Customer: “Red.”
Rep: “Nice colour! If the right deal came along, and we could get you a great value for your trade, would you consider trading your vehicle in?”

respuesta correcta Texto: B and C
feedbackText:
Make sure to use the pivotal Service Exchange trial close at the end of the test drive:

Question: What should be the first step in your Service Exchange sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): Welcome the customer into your sales funnel by using a friendly roadmap strategy, Explain the deals you want to present to your customer to the service advisor, Inform the service advisor of your customer’s arrival and get them to welcome the customer, Present your current service packages to the customer when they arrive in the service bay
respuesta correcta Texto: Welcome the customer into your sales funnel by using a friendly roadmap strategy
feedbackText:
Roadmapping a service exchange into a sale is a process involving many different aspects of your training.
You should follow a process similar to this:
Professionally welcome the Service Exchange customer into your sales funnel using a customer-friendly roadmap strategy.
Define and demonstrate control by effectively setting up and conducting a professional Service Exchange interview. Include road-mapping the "virtual evaluation" of the Service Exchange vehicle. See the Service Exchange Appointment Confirmations Knowledge Card for more information.
Explain SPACED to the customer and identify their Service Exchange hot buttons. See The SPACED Approach Knowledge Card for more information.
Identify the Service Exchange customer's needs and wants and successfully achieve selection by making a professional recommendation to the customer.
Plant the Service Exchange Value Price Promise to allow for holding the line. Confirm their affordability through the Service Exchange price proposal strategy. Include sharing their previous contract and highlight specific key areas; such as prior payment, down payment, etc. 
Roadmap professional SPACED  six-point Service Exchange walk-around making sure to take the time to sell the vehicle! Identify any complaints vs. real objections (deal breakers) during the SPACED vehicle walk-around. See the Step 4 of the Sale | Presentation Knowledge Card for more information.
Roadmap the demo drive and drive first, to demonstrate the vehicle!

Answer (from AnswerId): Listening to and identifying the customer’s needs and wants, Explaining the benefits of extended warranty, Offering better deals than your competitors, Presenting price breakdowns to the customer
respuesta correcta Texto: Listening to and identifying the customer’s needs and wants
feedbackText:

Roadmap professional SPACED  six-point Service Exchange walk-around making sure to take the time to sell the vehicle! Identify any complaints vs. real objections (deal breakers) during the SPACED vehicle walk-around. See the Step 4 of the Sale | Presentation Knowledge Card for more information.
Roadmap the demo drive and drive first, to demonstrate the vehicle!

Question: Asking for a customer’s desired means of communication allows them to feel _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): a sense of control that makes them more comfortable , a sense of fun in the shopping experience, like you don’t take the initiative to establish a clear communication method, like you’re asking too many personal questions
respuesta correcta Texto: a sense of control that makes them more comfortable
feedbackText:
After establishing contact with an interested buyer, make sure you say:
“Ms. Jones, we really appreciate you reaching out to us! I just want to make sure I can communicate with you in a way that works best for you. Would you feel more comfortable with texting, email, or phone calls?” 
Whatever Ms. Jones’ answer may be, it should be met with an enthusiastic, “Ok, perfect!” 
First, you gained clarity on how to interact positively with Ms. Jones. 
Secondly, you let her feel in control, which makes her feel more comfortable. 
Lastly, you are now transitioning to a direct form of communication through which Ms. Jones will more aptly respond.

Question: People would most prefer having a conversation with someone who makes them feel _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): comfortable, excited, calm, eager

feedbackText: When it comes to communicating with customers, you must do everything in your power to create the sense of comfort that they’re talking to a good friend.

Question:
Texting is the most streamlined form of communication with a customer. 
With that in mind, you should:
Answer (from AnswerId): Simply ask, “What means of communication do you prefer?” , Gently nudge the customer toward choosing text as their preferred communication, Kindly ask your customer if you can text them, Still avoid texting, because it crosses a personal line
respuesta correcta Texto: Simply ask, “What means of communication do you prefer?”
feedbackText:
How do you establish the customer’s preferred means of communication? You simply ask. 
It won’t be as awkward as you think, and they will genuinely appreciate it. For instance, after establishing contact with an interested buyer, make sure you say:
“Ms. Jones, we really appreciate you reaching out to us! I just want to make sure I can communicate with you in a way that works best for you. Would you feel more comfortable with texting, email, or phone calls?” 
Whatever Ms. Jones’ answer may be, it should be met with an enthusiastic, “Ok, perfect!”

Question: When discussing digital sales with a customer, you should use your own preferred means of communication to better convey information to your customers.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, False
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
When discussing digital sales with a potential customer, you can’t stick with your preferred method of communicating based on what makes you feel comfortable. This could inevitably result in customers shutting down because the customer may not prefer the same means of communication. 
They won’t feel comfortable, no matter how many exclamation points you put in your email or how chipper your tone on the phone.

Question: During a digital sale, why is it important to avoid having the conversation turn into an interrogation?
Answer (from AnswerId): Customers may not answer your questions correctly if they feel like they’re being interrogated, Customers may not provide you with a good referral if they feel like they’re being interrogated, Customers will look for a way to escape if they feel like they’re being interrogated, The middle portion of the sales process is supposed to involve a lot of questions
respuesta correcta Texto: Customers will look for a way to escape if they feel like they’re being interrogated
feedbackText:
During the digital sales process, your customers don’t want to be interrogated. 
Interrogations happen when ambitious sales people get so focused on closing deals that they plow over customers with a barrage of questions. Once your customer feels washed away by a sea of never-ending questions, they will frantically look for an escape from that torture.

respuesta correcta Texto: news and ideas are exchanged
feedbackText:
When discussing the concept of a conversation in the digital sales process, what do we mean by a “conversation”? 
“A talk, especially an informal one, between two or more people, in which news and ideas are exchanged.” 
“They had a conversation to plan out their vacation.” - [Oxford Dictionaries]

respuesta correcta Texto: Start a conversation with them to establish a connection
feedbackText: Once you have established the customer’s preferred method of communication, it’s time to spark a conversation.

Question: How can you keep the conversation moving and ease your customer’s tension?
Answer (from AnswerId): Ask your customer to tell you a story about their life, Speak at length about your customer’s interest, Talk to your customer about sports or the weather, Tell a short and amusing story
respuesta correcta Texto: Tell a short and amusing story
feedbackText:
When it comes to using proper selling techniques, if you’ll recall Core Selling Principle #2 (See the Being a Good Storyteller Concept for more information), telling a story brings people together, creates laughter, and eases tension. 
Stories are the oil in the conversation’s engine as they keep things running smoothly. 
Tell a short, amusing story to keep things moving and to ease your customer’s tension.

Question: Stories in the sales process could be described as _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): a great way to present yourself as an interesting person , the antifreeze for a cold conversation, an effective way to , the oil in a conversation’s engine
respuesta correcta Texto: the oil in a conversation’s engine
feedbackText:
When it comes to using proper selling techniques, if you’ll recall Core Selling Principle #2 (See the Being a Good Storyteller Concept for more information), telling a story brings people together, creates laughter, and eases tension. 
Stories are the oil in the conversation’s engine as they keep things running smoothly.

Question: What should you do as you’re roadmapping the conversation?
Answer (from AnswerId): Know whether they want to complete the transaction online or in-person, Make your customer aware of the exclusivity of the deal you’re offering, Establish their credit score, Ask your customer’s permission
respuesta correcta Texto: Ask your customer’s permission
feedbackText:
During the digital sales process, you roadmap by letting your customer know that you will be asking them some questions so that you have the most important details. Having these details will allow you to provide them with what they truly want and need. 
As you show them the roadmap, ask their permission to take them on that journey. For example: 
“Mr. Jones, I would like to start by asking you a few questions, so I can have a better understanding of how I can help you out today. Would that be okay with you?”

Question:
Which of these are questions to ask yourself  when practicing good self awareness?
A. Is your pace calm or rushed?
B. Do you sound interesting enough?
C. Is your tone aggressive or welcoming?
Answer (from AnswerId): A and C, A and B, B and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and C
feedbackText:
In order to create a conversation, you’ll still need to ask questions. There are two principles that will help keep your interaction a conversation rather than an interrogation and it’s important to follow these even during the digital sales process. 
Principle 1: Practice Self-AwarenessIs your pace calm or rushed? Is your tone aggressive or welcoming? Are you giving them a break from questions and adding value to their experience by sharing key information regarding the brand, the dealership, the product, and even yourself?

Question: Which of these best describes the process of roadmapping?
Answer (from AnswerId): Asking your customer a lot of questions , Telling your customer where you’ll be taking them on a test drive , Showing your customer as many cars as possible, Letting your customer know where the conversation is headed
respuesta correcta Texto: Letting your customer know where the conversation is headed
feedbackText:
In order to create a conversation, you’ll still need to ask questions. There are two principles that will help keep your interaction a conversation rather than an interrogation and it’s important to follow these even during the digital sales process. 
Principle 2: Roadmap the Conversation
There’s a reason your GPS gives a glimpse of your trip overview before beginning the step-by-step directions: you want to see where you’re headed before you get into the weeds. Your customers will also appreciate knowing where the conversation is headed rather than getting interrogated.  
This is called roadmapping. You roadmap by letting your customer know that you will be asking them some questions so that you have the most important details. Having these details will allow you to provide them with what they truly want and need.

Question: Which of these is NOT a characteristic that self-aware people practice?

respuesta correcta Texto: They get people to like them
feedbackText:
In order to create a conversation, you’ll still need to ask questions. There are two principles that will help keep your interaction a conversation rather than an interrogation and it’s important to follow these even during the digital sales process. 
Principle 1: Practice Self-AwarenessIs your pace calm or rushed? Is your tone aggressive or welcoming? Are you giving them a break from questions and adding value to their experience by sharing key information regarding the brand, the dealership, the product, and even yourself?

Question: Communicating scarcity in the sales process _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): gives you the flexibility to offer cars that may not include all of their preferences, helps establish reasonable expectations from your customer, is a best practice as it allows you to remain transparent with your customer  , should be kept at a minimum as it reflects poorly on your inventory
respuesta correcta Texto: gives you the flexibility to offer cars that may not include all of their preferences
feedbackText:
Whether your customer’s preferred vehicle is in high demand or short supply, you must make your customer aware of what’s unique about your selection and what they stand to lose if they don’t act now. 
As you get SPACED, establish a timeframe, and communicate scarcity, you have now gained flexibility. You are now positioned to present other options in trim or color to match your customer’s timeframe if necessary.

Question:
During the sales process, your customer mentions that they have a large, younger family.
Which of these aspects of SPACED do you think may be the most important to them?
Answer (from AnswerId): Safety, Appearance, Performance, Comfort
respuesta correcta Texto: Safety
feedbackText:
Use S.P.A.C.E.D to understand your customer's purchasing preferences: 
Safety
Performance
Appearance
Comfort
Economy
Dependability
Each of these words are a potential hot button preference. 
Your customer may not care about their vehicle’s appearance, but they may want to keep their kids safe in something that resembles a small tank. However, the 24-year-old who just got their first promotion may care much more about appearance.

Question: Establishing customer declarations isn’t a major factor in the sales process as long as you’re a good conversationalist.

respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
You may be the best conversationalist in town, but eventually you have to turn a corner. How do you transition from simply putting your customer at ease to obtaining the information needed for selling a car? 
Whether in-person or during the digital sales process, you must guide the customer to make clear declarations that will help you understand what they want. You can’t sell something when you don’t know what they need, want, or are looking for.

feedbackText:
The first declaration, which is especially important in digital sales, is do they want to complete this transaction online, or do they want to come into the dealership? 
After establishing your customer’s first declaration, it’s time to use S.P.A.C.E.D to understand their preferences: 
Safety
Performance
Appearance
Comfort
Economy
Dependability
Thirdly, determine their timeframe by asking the following: 
“Ms. Jones, I want to make sure I am meeting all your needs, so what is your purchase timeframe?”
Once you’ve gotten SPACED and you know their timeframe, it’s time to utilize one of your greatest weapons: Scarcity (See the Six Weapons of Influence Concept for more information).

Question: After listening to your customer discuss their payment options, what is the next step in the digital sales process?

Question: Customers have significant leverage when contacting a dealership online because they know they have options.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: True
feedbackText:
Speed is everything when it comes to responding to E-leads (electronic leads that have come through the dealership website or another social channel). 
Each potential customer wants your help, but they also have options. 
When they connect with your dealership online, do they feel like they’re connecting with someone who they can trust? 
A near immediate response should be the standard, because it’s your fighting chance in an extremely competitive landscape. 
The goal is to provide your customers with a response in 10 minutes or less. This will show initiative and that you’re responsive to their needs.
However, here’s the bad news. A lot of dealerships know this, and they’re getting really good at it.

Question: What is important to remember while responding quickly to e-leads?
Answer (from AnswerId): Be personable, Include your current promotions, Offer multiple vehicle choices, Showcase your experience
respuesta correcta Texto: Be personable
feedbackText:
To hold your own, you must strike the balance between delivering an immediate, yet personalized response. 
You wouldn’t be very interested in someone who introduced themselves as:
“Hi I’m Bob. I sell cars. I’ve done it for years.”
Bye Bob. I’m going to find someone who isn’t a robot. You would be much more willing to discuss your needs with someone who introduced themselves as:
“Hi! I’m Bob. I love fishing, hiking, and ‘I Don’t Want to Wait’ by Paula Cole is my guilty pleasure song.”
This shows a real human who a customer might actually have something in common with, rather than someone who only sees themselves as a conveyor belt of cars.

Question: Detecting and addressing what a customer wants in an e-lead is known as finding their _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): buyer type, immediate need, pain point, struggle position
respuesta correcta Texto: immediate need
feedbackText:
It’s important to listen to what the customer actually wants. This takes practice, but you can actually listen to an email. 
It’s unbelievable how many sales reps miss opportunities because of their inability to listen to the customer from the very outset. 
You can develop the ability to listen by:
Picturing the customer sitting in front of you as you read their email or text. This is a real person who’s calling for help!
Asking yourself, “What does this person want?” You can call this their immediate need. Listen, ask questions, and define what their immediate need is. Let them know that you want to work with them in fulfilling their immediate needs, and that you’re there to help.

Question: How can you create a sense of immediacy in your initial response to an e-lead?
Answer (from AnswerId): Include “limited time offer” in the subject line of your response back to them, Include a set of pricing options on the vehicle that the customer is interested in, Include your dealership’s current deals and promotions, Inform the customer that they have limited time to respond to your message
respuesta correcta Texto: Include your dealership’s current deals and promotions
feedbackText:
While crafting an initial response, remember to ask whether or not they have a vehicle to trade-in. Many customers will not include their trade information in their initial inquiry. 
Asking qualifying questions in your response can help you determine the deals are available to them or which way you may have to take the conversation:
“Are you presently driving a vehicle that you are looking to trade-in or sell privately?”
You can then follow this up with additional leading questions, such as:
“Would you consider trading your vehicle with us, if the right deal came along?”
“What do you like most about your vehicle?”
You’ll also want to create a sense of immediacy. In your initial response, let them see the deals your dealership is offering, and this may urge them to move forward with you as their rep.

feedbackText:

Including a photo signature with your response will help personalize the interaction. You create a “physical experience” for the customer by putting a face to your name. This will ensure that your reply doesn’t blend in with other dealership’s responses too.
Make sure to include a short bio about yourself that gives a glimpse of who you really are as a person.
Be sure to use the customer’s name and reference their vehicle of interest in the subject line as well. This will immediately stand out when they receive your response and make it more likely that they’ll read the message.

Question: Which of these questions should you consider during the Selection stage to identify what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with?
Answer (from AnswerId): Did your salesperson present a peace of mind package?, Did your salesperson sell the vehicle?, Did the first impression of the sale take place?, Did your salesperson drive it first? (If within COVID-19 guidelines)
respuesta correcta Texto: Did your salesperson present a peace of mind package?
feedbackText:
When it comes to identifying what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with, there are several questions you should consider at different stages in the process.
Selection
During the selection process, you should know:
Did your salesperson build conviction and confirm the customer’s selection? 
Did they ask menu price presentation questions? 
Did they read the value price?
Did they present a peace of mind package?

Question: Which of these questions should you consider during the Presentation stage to identify what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with?
Answer (from AnswerId): Did your salesperson sell the vehicle?, Did the first impression of the sale take place?, Did your salesperson drive it first? (If within COVID-19 guidelines), Did your salesperson present a peace of mind package?
respuesta correcta Texto: Did your salesperson sell the vehicle?
feedbackText:
When it comes to identifying what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with, there are several questions you should consider at different stages in the process.
Presentation
When into the presentation stage of the sales process, ask yourself:
Did your salesperson sell the vehicle?
What hot button features did they present?
Are there any deal breakers?
Are they focused on condition-based or feature, benefit, advantage-based selling (depending on whether its a used or new vehicle)

Question: Which of these questions should you consider during the Demonstration stage to identify what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with?
Answer (from AnswerId): Did your salesperson drive it first? (If within COVID-19 guidelines), Did the first impression of the sale take place?, Did your salesperson sell the vehicle?, Did your salesperson present a peace of mind package?
respuesta correcta Texto: Did your salesperson drive it first? (If within COVID-19 guidelines)
feedbackText:
When it comes to identifying what kind of buyer your salesperson is working with, there are several questions you should consider at different stages in the process.
Demonstration
At the vehicle demonstration, you should know:
Did your salesperson drive it first? (If within COVID-19 guidelines)
What did they demonstrate?
How did the customer enjoy the drive? 
Did your salesperson set up the evaluation and remain quiet? 
Did they utilize a trial close?

Are they going to be servicing their vehicle here?

Question: As a sales manager, what should your role be during the sales process?
Answer (from AnswerId): To ensure that you avoid giving the customer a price too early, To help the salesperson move immediately to pricing, To only confirm the trade, test drive, and commitment from the customer, To stay completely involved in the process
respuesta correcta Texto: To stay completely involved in the process
feedbackText:
Managing the first five steps of the sales process (meet and greet, interview, selection, presentation, and demonstration drive) creates a significant area of opportunity.
Staying Involved in the Process
Many sales managers make the mistake of only confirming the trade, test drive, and commitment from the customer, then move immediately into pricing. Or, they make an even bigger mistake of not giving the customer a price at all!

Question:
Which of these are examples of bad questions you should avoid asking your salespeople during the sales process?
A. "Hey, how is it going with your customer?" 
B. "Does the customer have a trade?" 
C. "Did the customer drive it?"
Answer (from AnswerId): All of the above, B and C, A and B, A and C
respuesta correcta Texto: All of the above
feedbackText:
Many sales managers make the mistake of only confirming the trade, test drive, and commitment from the customer, then move immediately into pricing. Or, they make an even bigger mistake of not giving the customer a price at all! 
Here’s an example of what not to ask as a sales manager:
"Hey, how is it going with your customer?" 
"Do they have a trade?" 
"Did they drive it?" 
"Do you have commitment?" 
"No? Ok, tell them to come back when they are ready to buy and make sure you give them your business card." 
Reflecting on this interaction:
Did your salesperson sell themself? 
Did your salesperson sell the dealership? 
Did your salesperson sell your brand? 
Did your salesperson even sell the product?

Question: If you want to maximize all of your sales opportunities, you should take the time to collaborate with your salespeople.
Answer (from AnswerId): True, False
respuesta correcta Texto: True
feedbackText:
If you want to maximize all of your sales opportunities, direct your focus on the first five steps of the sale and dig into the interview with your salespeople. Take the time to collaborate with them. 
By working together collectively, you’ll have a better understanding of your customer's buyer motivations and how you can help your salesperson close the deal!

Question: As a sales manager, what can you do during the sales process to have a more qualified customer while creating accountability with your salespeople?
Answer (from AnswerId): Both of the above, Ask to see evidence of the customer interview, Create discussion points around the steps of the sale, Neither of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: Both of the above
feedbackText:
If you ask to see evidence of the customer interview, and create discussion points around the steps of the sale, you will have a more qualified customer. 
The interview will also start to represent part of your salesperson’s report card. They will grow to know that you are going to review it with them every time a customer comes into the dealership.

Question: Why is it important to create expectations of your salespeople to ask the right questions?
Answer (from AnswerId): To ultimately get the results you’re looking for, To ensure every sale has a high gross profit margin, To make your salespeople’s performance reviews easier, To set up more bbacks
respuesta correcta Texto: To ultimately get the results you’re looking for
feedbackText:
The interview will also start to represent part of your salesperson’s report card. They will grow to know that you are going to review it with them every time a customer comes into the dealership. 
This added accountability will motivate them to complete more aspects of the sales process and better set you up at the desk.
If you don't create these expectations by asking the right questions, you will never get the result that you are hoping for. Stop hoping and start doing!

Question: When it comes to creating accountability during the sales process, the customer interview will also start to represent part of your salesperson’s _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): report card, accountability report, closing technique, performance evaluation
respuesta correcta Texto: report card
feedbackText:
If you ask to see evidence of the customer interview, and create discussion points around the steps of the sale, you will have a more qualified customer. 
The interview will also start to represent part of your salesperson’s report card. They will grow to know that you are going to review it with them every time a customer comes into the dealership.

C. Suggest they tell the customer you will be available in about 10 to 12 minutes and that they could use that time for a quick test drive
Answer (from AnswerId): All of the above, B and C, A and C, A and B
respuesta correcta Texto: All of the above
feedbackText:
Expect that your salespeople are always going to miss certain things in the sales process. To help identify the areas of opportunity, fill those gaps in the process through selling time!
In the mentioned scenario, you should praise them for the great job they’ve done so far, lead with questions to gain an understanding of why the test drive did not take place, then, suggest something like the following to help your salesperson get that test drive: 
Salesperson: "Great news! My sales manager is more than happy to get you some detailed pricing. However, they’re just finalizing another deal, and it could take about 10 to 12 minutes. Are you ok to wait?"
Customer: "Sure, I don't mind waiting."
Salesperson: "Terrific! While we are waiting, why don't I pull the vehicle around and we can head out for a quick test drive! How does that sound?"

Question: What’s the procedure your salesperson should take if a customer states that they don’t have the time for a test drive?
Answer (from AnswerId): Your salesperson should come back, touch desk, and you would then move into managing the price, Your salesperson should move directly into managing the price, Your salesperson should ask the customer to be back when they have more time, Any of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: Your salesperson should come back, touch desk, and you would then move into managing the price
feedbackText: If the customer states that they don’t have the time, your salesperson would come back, touch desk, and you would then move into managing the price.

Question: Many people don't make it in the vehicle sales industry because of their inability to:
Answer (from AnswerId): Overcome rejection, Close sales everytime, Convince the customer, Create opportunities
respuesta correcta Texto: Overcome rejection
feedbackText: For your salespeople to become successful sales professionals, they need to understand that many people don't make it in the vehicle sales industry because of their inability to overcome rejection.

Question: What are trained salespeople expecting and prepared to deal with?
Answer (from AnswerId): “No” answers, Bargain-focused customers, High stress reactions, Walk-away threats
respuesta correcta Texto: “No” answers
feedbackText:
Dealing with constant rejection is par for the course, but overcoming constant rejection takes training and practice! Trained salespeople are both expecting and prepared to deal with a “no” answer. Once the “no” is uncovered, it is time to ask why not today.
Keep in mind to let your salespeople know that customers are sometimes sensitive in these situations. If they begin feeling too much pressure, they can move into high stress quickly, become frustrated, and simply shut down. 
This leads to them walking away and not returning. Therefore, it is not as easy as just asking why not today if you don't want to scare them away.

Question: Which of these questions should you ask yourself while coaching your staff?
Answer (from AnswerId): All of the above, Do your salespeople know how to uncover root objections?, How many closes do they have available and ready to help close the deal?, What does the right balance of empathy and persistence look like?
respuesta correcta Texto: All of the above
feedbackText:
The definition of perseverance is:
“Persistence in doing something despite difficulty or delay in achieving success.” 
Some questions to ask yourself when coaching your staff include:
What does the right balance of empathy and persistence look like? 
Do your salespeople know how to uncover root objections? 
How many closes do they have available and ready to help close the deal? 
Much like martial arts, the higher the degree, the higher the skill set, and the higher the result!

Question: The only way you can enter into exit management planning is through:
Answer (from AnswerId): Customer rejection, Any of the above, Failure to close, Customer acceptance
respuesta correcta Texto: Customer rejection
feedbackText: The only way you can enter into exit management planning is through customer rejection.

Question: If you send your salesperson out with a 84-month finance option, based on $0 down and no options for the customer to compare to, they’re likely to accept the initial set of numbers and agree to purchase the vehicle on the spot.
Answer (from AnswerId): False, True
respuesta correcta Texto: False
feedbackText:
Giving the customer multiple options, inclusive of shorter terms and down payment options, is the key.
Customers usually walk away if they are offered only choice and head home! It’s crucial to understand that the rejection of one option will always lead to the acceptance of another!

Question: After presenting the numbers to a customer to evoke a decision, your salespeople need to:
Answer (from AnswerId): Ask for the sale, Be subtle and ask the customer what they think of the offer, Tell the customer they will only get a discount if they buy today, Wait for the customer to decide
respuesta correcta Texto: Ask for the sale
feedbackText:
After presenting the numbers to the customer to evoke a decision, your salespeople also need to ask for the sale.
Many salespeople will present numbers to a customer and not even ask for the order out of forgetfulness or fear of rejection. Many sales managers assume that their salespeople ask for the order every time, when they actually don't.

Question: As a salesperson, if you’re not able to generate an offer, you can’t begin the _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): negotiations, delivery process, selection process, vehicle presentation
respuesta correcta Texto: negotiations
feedbackText:
As a salesperson, your job is to generate offers. If you aren't able to generate an offer, you can't begin the negotiations. 
In order to successfully negotiate, you must be able to identify which area of the price is the most important to the customer. It’s critical that we're able to isolate to a unit of one. If the customer is trying to negotiate the price, their trade value, and the term length, you're climbing an uphill battle that won't likely end in a sale.

Question:
While working with a customer on a new deal, they ask if you can tint the windows for free. 
Using the differing to higher authority closing technique, how should you respond?
Answer (from AnswerId): “As a salesperson, I am only allowed to sell the vehicle at the value price. However, if I can confirm the tint at no charge with my sales manager, would we have a deal today?", “As a salesperson, I’m normally only allowed to sell the vehicle at the value price. However, I’ll make an exception if we have a deal today?”, “Unfortunately, as a salesperson, I’m only allowed to sell the vehicle at the value price. I could ask my sales manager though; would we then have a deal today?”, None of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: “As a salesperson, I am only allowed to sell the vehicle at the value price. However, if I can confirm the tint at no charge with my sales manager, would we have a deal today?"
feedbackText:
Rather than confirm whether or not you can do a certain price or payment, you should work from a position of strength. When the customer asks “Do you think you can include the tinted windows for free?" Take the customer's side against management. Share that you would like to, and explain: 
“As a salesperson, I am only allowed to sell the vehicle at the value price. In wanting to tailor this deal to your needs, if I can confirm the tint at no charge with my sales manager, would we have a deal today?"
If the customer says yes, you have an offer! Now you’re working from a position of strength; meaning that it’s up to your sales manager if you have a deal or not. They can say “yes” or “no” to the deal instead of the customer just asking for a copy of the price quote and walking.

Question: Many salespeople make the mistake of confirming whether or not they think they can do a deal without gaining _______ from the customer.
Answer (from AnswerId): commitment, documentation, sympathy, trust
respuesta correcta Texto: commitment
feedbackText:
Many salespeople make the mistake of confirming whether or not they think they can do a deal without gaining commitment from the customer. The customer, now knowing what you can do, will ask for a copy of your price quote, then shop your price around and go to your competition. 
Rather than confirm whether or not you can do a certain price or payment, you should work from a position of strength. When the customer asks “Do you think you can include the tinted windows for free?" Take the customer's side against management and ask for commitment.

Working from a position of strength will make a huge difference when it comes to increasing both your gross profits and closing ratio!

Question:
What is the purpose of using the direct closing technique?
A. To gain commitment from the customer
B. To create the rejection of one of the available options
C. To provide the customer with more options
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, B and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and B
feedbackText:
The direct closing technique can be effective for gaining commitment. 
This technique can be used to close the deal or, as it’s more commonly used, to create rejection with the understanding that the rejection of one option will always lead to the acceptance of another.

Question: When you offer the customer a question that requires an answer in order to move forward in the sales process, it’s called:
Answer (from AnswerId): Direct closing, Anxiety closing, Dream deal closing, Bracketing
respuesta correcta Texto: Direct closing
feedbackText:
The direct closing technique can be effective for gaining commitment. 
This technique can be used to close the deal or, as it’s more commonly used, to create rejection with the understanding that the rejection of one option will always lead to the acceptance of another. 
Confirming a customer's position based on their initial reaction and potential rejection of the direct closing question can actually lead to closing a sale. For example: 
Salesperson: "Mr. and Mrs. Jones, provided I can confirm a bottom line of $32,389, would we have a deal today?"
By doing this, you’ve offered them a direct question that requires an answer in order to move forward in the process; regardless of whether or not they want to accept this specific offer.

respuesta correcta Texto: “Provided I can confirm a bottom line of $36,529, would we have a deal today?"

Confirming a customer's position based on their initial reaction and potential rejection of the direct closing question can actually lead to closing a sale. For example:

By doing this, you’ve offered them a direct question that requires an answer in order to move forward in the process; regardless of whether or not they want to accept this specific offer.

Question: Creating a higher or lower positioning of price, depending on whether you are buying or selling, is known as:

respuesta correcta Texto: Bracketing
feedbackText: Creating a higher or lower positioning of price, depending on whether you are buying or selling, is known as building brackets or bracketing.

Question: With regards to bracketing, someone might list or say their vehicle is worth more than what it actually is to provide them with an advantage while _______.
Answer (from AnswerId): negotiating, discussing purchase price, leasing, receiving an appraisal
respuesta correcta Texto: negotiating
feedbackText:
An example of creating a bracket would be if you decide to sell your home and know you want at least $850,000 for it. In wanting to hit your target price, you decide to list your home for $960,000. 
Understanding that the individual who may want to purchase your home is going to negotiate, you’ve now created a $110,000 bracket to give yourself the advantage while negotiating.
In vehicle sales, many customers will do this by asking for a higher trade value than what their vehicle is actually worth. They essentially inflate the value, knowing that they've left themselves some room to come down.

Question: In vehicle sales, an example of bracketing is when a customer asks for a higher trade value than what their vehicle is actually worth.

Question:
Which of these are factors that customers like to consider before making a final decision to purchase or lease a vehicle?
A. The overall quality of the product
B. The price
C. Their servicing needs
Answer (from AnswerId): All of the above, B and C, A and C, A and B
respuesta correcta Texto: All of the above
feedbackText:
For customers, it's not always easy to make the right decision when it comes to purchasing or leasing a vehicle. Many customers like to consider three major factors before making a final decision: 
The first is the overall quality of the product they are considering
Secondly, many customers have questions about their servicing needs, such as hours of operation, shuttle service, etc. 
Lastly is the price; most customers want to make sure they are getting the best price 
Knowing that these are the main factors in a customer’s decision will help you uncover their root objection in the sales process more easily.

Question: When the customer holds off and says “not today” for a deal, what should the salesperson do?

“Not today” is a feeling or mindset. This mindset can be changed if you offer additional value by asking the right questions, listening, and eventually sharing solution-based options that help solve the customer's problem.

Question:

A. "Can I say not to go below $8,500?"

Question: Which of these questions could you ask the customer to narrow their choices down to one trim level only?
Answer (from AnswerId): Any of the above, Would you like to know about our standard warranty coverage?, What does typical driving look like throughout the week versus the weekend?, Are you the principal driver?
respuesta correcta Texto: Any of the above
feedbackText:
This may seem unimportant, but there are several factors in a customer’s lifestyle that could affect which vehicle trim they choose.
The interview questions below represent some good qualifying conversation starters. You’ll find that you may want to add some as you continue throughout the conversation and become a more experienced interviewer. 
At the end of the interview, the goal is to narrow the customer’s choices down to one trim level only.
Some key interview questions include:
How many K.M.'s at delivery?
How many now?
Based on the K.M.'s you drive, are you aware you are a lease candidate? (40,000 or less is a good benchmark)
Are you the principal driver?
Will there be anyone else who needs to help with selecting the colour and trim level?
What does typical driving look like throughout the week versus the weekend?
Any big road trips coming up?
How many members are in your family?
Any pets travelling with you?
How important is cargo space?
Do you use your vehicle for work?
Any special requirements? For example, winter tires, bike rack or a trailer hitch?
Are you planning on servicing your new vehicle at our location?
Would you like to know about our standard warranty coverage?
Agreement to trim level at the end of the interview is the fourth customer commitment.

Question:
What could happen if a customer’s stress level is too high after the test drive and you’re not able to guide them back inside?
A. They may leave
B. You may never see them again
C. You may have to work harder to close on the bback
Answer (from AnswerId): A and B, A and C, B and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and B
feedbackText:
Once they return from their test drive, make sure you trial close to detailed pricing:
Salesperson: "Welcome back! How did you enjoy the test drive?"
Customer: "Fine."
Don’t put too much stock on your customer’s response after the test drive. Their emotional state could be starting to increase to a level of high stress. They may believe they have to buy the vehicle if they head inside.
If their stress level is too high, they may leave and you will typically never see them again. If you can't guide your customer back inside after the test drive, the numerical negotiations never occur, and all is lost.
Salesperson: "Is this the model that you would like me to work out some detailed pricing on? That way, you can take the numbers home and think things over."
Customer: "That would be great."
You’ve gained the tenth commitment from your customer; they’re willing to go over detailed pricing with you.

Question: What does the third commitment in the sales process involve?

respuesta correcta Texto: Confirming a value appraisal if the customer has a vehicle to trade
feedbackText:
The third commitment in the sales process is contingent on whether or not the customer has a vehicle to trade; confirming a value appraisal. 
Note: Be sure to follow all COVID-19 guidelines to ensure a safe interaction between yourself and the customer.

Question: After confirming the customer’s contact information and beginning to take notes, you’ll want to move into discussing:
Answer (from AnswerId): Their current vehicle, if applicable, The form of payment, Their budget, None of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: Their current vehicle, if applicable
feedbackText:
After confirming their contact information and beginning to take notes, you’ll want to move into discussing their current vehicle right away. Many negotiations are won or lost right at this moment.
What does your customer want to do with their current vehicle? Anyone who is willing to trade their vehicle can automatically be considered a conditional buyer.
You need to find a way to have them let you do a vehicle appraisal. For example:
Salesperson: "Can I ask what you’re driving now?"
Customer: "We’re driving a 2010 Toyota Corolla C.E."
Salesperson: "Would you consider trading it?"
Customer: "No, we are going to sell it privately."
Salesperson: "I understand you are not trading your vehicle, could we buy it from you then?"
Customer: "What is the difference?"
Salesperson: "Good question! When you trade your vehicle, typically, the entire value of the trade is taken from the new vehicle's principal amount. When we buy your car, you can take your vehicle's entire value and put it right back in your bank account. We find with interest rates so low; many customers are taking that value and paying down their line of credit or credit cards! Could I at least get you an opinion of what your vehicle might be worth?
Customer: "Sounds interesting; why not."
You’ve now gotten the third commitment out of your customer; they’re allowing you to perform a value appraisal.

Question:
At the beginning of the sales process, once you’ve introduced yourself to your customer, you should take a mental pause and listen to them to determine:
A. How much the customer is willing to spend
B. What kind of buyer type they are
C. What the customer wants to accomplish
Answer (from AnswerId): B and C, A and B, A and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: B and C
feedbackText:
Once you’ve introduced yourself to your customer, you should take a mental pause and listen to them to determine what kind of buyer type they are (timid, average, or supreme). 
You should also be listening to what the customer wants to accomplish today: 
What is the customer's mission? 
What are the customers' immediate needs? 
Is it a brochure? 
Is it a test drive?

Answer (from AnswerId): Confirming that the customer will be interviewed, Taking notes from the customer to ensure you have all the appropriate information from them, Understanding which of the items in the SPACED concept are the most important to the customer, None of the above

Question: Once you know what type of buyer your customer is and what they want to accomplish, what should you do to confirm the first commitment?
Answer (from AnswerId): Roadmap for control, Confirm the customer’s vehicle selection, Present the customer with 3 vehicles that match their needs, Tell them you must get all the appropriate information from them before you can show them anything
respuesta correcta Texto: Roadmap for control
feedbackText:
During the interview, you’ll want to confirm the correct spelling of the customer's first and last name and gather two phone numbers along with an email address.
Your customer knows what they want; they’re an average buyer and have no issues making decisions. 
You must now roadmap for control. It’s now time to confirm the first commitment.
Salesperson: "Welcome again, Chris! Typically, I like to start by bringing my customers back to my fully sanitized workstation to discuss their needs and wants and talk about what they’re currently driving right now. Would that be ok with you?"
Customer: "Sure." 
Just like that, you’ve gotten the first commitment out of your customer; they’re willing to be interviewed.

Question:
Which of these should be included in the six-point walkaround when you reach the eighth commitment in the sales process?
A. Overall view and cargo area 
B. Rear passenger side and front passenger
C. Under the hood and the driver seat
Answer (from AnswerId): All of the above, B and C, A and C, A and B
respuesta correcta Texto: All of the above
feedbackText:
When you reach the eighth commitment, your customer's emotions are still at a level of controlled stress. They’re now probably in a decision-making state.
It’s now time for a six-point walkaround:
Overall view
Cargo area 
Rear passenger side
Front passenger 
Under the hood
Driver seat
Remember to focus on the SPACED areas the customer highlighted to you previously. 
Roadmap your walkaround as well; you need to continue to sell the vehicle and not just show it. Each position allows you to gain additional commitment:
Salesperson: “Here is the brand new X model! We know this is a big decision. To make it easier, I’ll break the vehicle down into six different sections and ask you if each area meets your approval. How does that sound?
Customer: "Ok, let's check it out."
You’ve gained the eighth commitment from the customer; they want you to walk through the vehicle with them.

Question: By using the acronym SPACED (Safety, Performance, Appearance, Comfort, Economy, Dependability), with your customer, you can easily identify what areas of the vehicle are most important to them.
Answer (from AnswerId): True, False
respuesta correcta Texto: True
feedbackText:
By using the acronym SPACED (Safety, Performance, Appearance, Comfort, Economy, Dependability), with your customer, you can easily identify what is most important to them. For example:
Salesperson: “SPACED is an acronym that we like to use. As you can see, it stands for safety, performance, appearance, comfort, economy, and dependability. I take the time to share this with you because when I go to show you the vehicle, I can tailor the presentation and demonstration to your specific needs. How does that sound?
Customer: "Good."
Salesperson: "Considering these important factors, which one would be most important? What would be your close second? And if there had to be a third?"
Customer: “Probably safety, performance, and comfort.”
Understanding which of the SPACED areas are most important to your customer is the fifth major commitment.

Salesperson: "Just before I work out some detailed pricing, many customers ask me, if they should buy or lease their next vehicle? We have put together this short presentation so that you can answer that question yourself. Can I take a few minutes to share it with you?"

Review the final vehicle selection breakdown and make sure to include all accessories and protection packages your customer requested.
Have your customer initial that the vehicle's equipment meets their requirements and that they want the detailed pricing:
Salesperson: "I just wanted to let you know about all your options. We also believe that price has become so important that it needs to be in writing, would you agree?"
Customer: "Yes, most definitely."

Question:
Taking notes on the customer’s information during the sales process will make them notice that:
A. You are listening
B. You are motivated to sell
C. You are focused on their needs
Answer (from AnswerId): A and C, A and B, B and C, All of the above
respuesta correcta Texto: A and C
feedbackText:
You want to make sure you take the time to document the customer's information. The customer will notice that you are listening and that you are focused on their needs. 
This will also serve as a great tool when sharing information with your sales manager and following up afterwards.
Salesperson: "I would like to take the time to make some notes so that I won't forget anything, would that be ok?"
Customer: "Sure.”
You’ve now gotten the second commitment out of your customer; you’re taking notes on their information.

Question: During the sales process, acknowledging that you’re happy to get the customer detailed pricing and set up a test drive means their emotions have likely come down to a level of:
Answer (from AnswerId): Controlled apathy, Controlled worry, Immediate relaxation, Moderate anxiety
respuesta correcta Texto: Controlled apathy
feedbackText:
After redirecting the customer to your workstation and confirming the interview, you’ll be able to better qualify them by gathering more information. Acknowledging that you’re happy to get them detailed pricing and set up a test drive means their emotions have likely come down to a level of controlled apathy. 
They’re likely feeling more relaxed and are probably more open to sharing information.

Question: Assessing your customer’s body language to determine their level of comfort and find out what buyer type they may represent is _______ before you greet them.
Answer (from AnswerId): important, unnecessary
respuesta correcta Texto: important
feedbackText:
You should assess the customer’s body language to determine their level of comfort and find out what buyer type they may represent. Then, with a positive attitude, greet the customer.
Please see an example scenario below:
Your customer enters the showroom and approaches a new vehicle. Their emotions are likely at a level of controlled stress. 
You assess their body language and with a positive attitude, you greet the customer:
Salesperson: "Good morning! Welcome to Hometown Motors. My name is _______, and you are?" 
Customer: "Chris Jones. You can call me Chris." 
Salesperson:"Nice to meet you, Chris! Is there a particular vehicle I can show you today?
Customer: "I want to take the XX model for a test drive and get some pricing."
Salesperson: "Absolutely! I’m more than happy to get you some detailed pricing. We have a number of those models in stock, and they have all been freshly sanitized. Would you like to drive one with leather or cloth interior?" 
Customer: "Good to know. I was hoping to drive the Sport model."
Salesperson: "Very nice choice, Chris! I will be happy to pull the Sport model around and give it one final wipe down for you. Just before I do, is this your first visit to our dealership, or do you have an appointment today?"
Customer: "I do not have an appointment booked, and yes, it is my first visit."

Question: When introducing the customer to the vehicle’s price, reading your Value Pricing Policy to them is:
Answer (from AnswerId): Crucial, Unnecessary, Forbidden, Optional
respuesta correcta Texto: Crucial
feedbackText:
Based on your previous interview answers, you’ve now confirmed the correct trim level and can use this opportunity to confirm their affordability by introducing price. 
It’s a crucial best practice to read your Value Pricing Policy to your customer, which suggests that the M.S.R.P. is the best price and no negotiations are required.  It represents no-hassle pricing similar to what some other retailers refer to as "Integrity Pricing." 
You should have a laminated copy at your workstation and a digital version that you can pull up and share with your customers at any time:
Salesperson: "Terrific! When we head outside to look at the vehicle, I will focus on those SPACED areas. Just before we head outside, has anyone taken the time to share "X manufacturer's" value pricing?"
Customer: "No, what is that?"
Introducing the value pricing to your customer represents the sixth major commitment.

Salesperson: "Terrific! When we head outside to look at the vehicle, I will focus on those SPACED areas. Just before we head outside, has anyone taken the time to share "X manufacturer's" value pricing?"
Customer: "No, what is that?"
Introducing the value pricing to your customer represents the sixth major commitment.

Question: What’s the first step in creating a Service Exchange package?
Answer (from AnswerId): Determine the retail value of a customer’s vehicle using VAuto, Determine what trades you need on your lot, Print out a price proposal on a brand new model with a comparable trim level, Print out a virtual value appraisal voucher on a specific vehicle model
respuesta correcta Texto: Determine the retail value of a customer’s vehicle using VAuto
feedbackText:
Creating packages of service exchange options helps simplify the sales process for your SE specialists. 
To create an SE package, use the following process: 
Using VAuto, determine the retail value of a customer’s vehicle and print out the competitive retail set that highlights the vehicle that is most comparable to their vehicle.
Determine the wholesale value of the vehicle and print the VAuto trade appraisal voucher. Use a cheque format based on the wholesale value. Note: The appraisal voucher should represent "virtual value" only and is subject to a final, physical appraisal.
Print out a copy of the customer's current contract and highlight their current payment, down payment, previous trade value, interest rate, terms, and any products that they purchased last time.
Print out a price proposal on a brand new model, based on a comparable trim level, and using the same parameters as their last contract. Include multiple lease and finance term options and make sure to highlight the down payment, trade value, interest rate, terms that are the same as their previous contract, and any products included in the price.
Create urgency using a print out advertising the SE incentive you have running at that particular point in time. It can be related to test drives, making a lease or purchase the same-day, or within the next couple of days.

feedbackText: When building your Service Exchange packages, create a minimum of five SE packages for each of the next three days. Be sure to cherry-pick the trades you want on your lot!
